&s;s</HI> of his <HI>dear Son,</HI> awaits you.&mdash;<HI>See</HI> it, <HI>view</HI> it <HI>again</HI> and <HI>again.</HI>&mdash;Con&s;ider at <HI>how dear a Rate</HI> it was <HI>purcha&s;ed,</HI> even by <HI>the Blood</HI> of God.&mdash;Con&s;ider <HI>what great Need</HI> you have of it.&mdash;You are <HI>lo&s;t, undone, damned for ever,</HI> without it!&mdash;Come then, <HI>poor, guilty Prodigals,</HI> come <HI>home.</HI>&mdash;Indeed
<PB N="26" REF="005311_0033_10180EC713232F68">
I will not, like the <HI>elder Brother,</HI> be angry&mdash;<HI>No,</HI> I will <HI>rejoice</HI> with the <HI>Angels</HI> in <HI>Heaven</HI> And Oh, that God would now <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ow the Heaven and come down!</HI> <Q>De&s;cend, <HI>O Son of God,</HI> de|&s;cend; and as thou ha&s;t &s;hewn in <HI>me</HI> &s;uch Mercy, O let thy <HI>ble&s;&s;ed Spirit</HI> apply <HI>thy Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> to <HI>&s;ome young Prodigals</HI> now <HI>be|fore thee,</HI> and clothe their <HI>naked Souls</HI> with thy <HI>be&s;t</HI> Robe.</Q></P>
<P>But I mu&s;t &s;peak a Word to you, <HI>young Maidens,</HI> as well as <HI>young Men.</HI>&mdash;I &s;ee <HI>many</HI> of you <HI>adorned;</HI> as to your <HI>Bodies:</HI>&mdash;But are not your <HI>Souls</HI> naked? <HI>Which</HI> of you can &s;ay, the <HI>Lord</HI> is <HI>my Righteou&s;ne&s;s?</HI> Which of you was <HI>ever &s;olicitous</HI> to be <HI>dre&s;&s;ed</HI> in <HI>this Robe</HI> of <HI>invaluable</HI> Price, and <HI>without which,</HI> you are no better than <HI>whited Sepulchres</HI> in the Sight of God?&mdash;Let not then <HI>&s;o many</HI> of you; <HI>Young Maidens,</HI> any longer forget your <HI>only ornament.</HI>&mdash;Oh, &s;eek for the <HI>Lord</HI> to be <HI>your Righteou&s;ne&s;s,</HI> or otherwi&s;e <HI>Burn|ing</HI> will &s;oon be <HI>upon you,</HI> in&s;tead of <HI>Beauty!</HI></P>
<P>And what &s;hall I &s;ay to <HI>you</HI> of a <HI>middle Age,</HI> you <HI>bu&s;y Merchants,</HI> you <HI>cumber'd Martha's,</HI> who, with <HI>all your Gettings,</HI> have not <HI>yet gotten</HI> the <HI>Lord</HI> to be <HI>your</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s? Alas! what <HI>Profit</HI> will there be of <HI>all your Labuor</HI> under the Sun, if you do not <HI>&s;ecure</HI> this Pearl of <HI>invaluable</HI> Price? This <HI>one</HI> Thing, &s;o <HI>ab&s;olutely needful,</HI> that it <HI>only</HI> can &s;tand you in &s;tead, when <HI>all other Things</HI> &s;hall be taken <HI>from</HI> you. Labour there|fore no longer &s;o <HI>anxiou&s;ly</HI> for the Meat <HI>which peri&s;heth,</HI> but <HI>henceforward</HI> &s;eek for the <HI>Lord</HI> to be <HI>your Righteou&s;ne&s;s,</HI>&mdash;A <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> that will
<PB N="27" REF="005311_0034_10180EC9854A08D0">
<HI>intitle you</HI> to <HI>Life everla&s;ting.</HI>&mdash;I &s;ee al&s;o many <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Heads</HI> here, and perhaps the <HI>mo&s;t of</HI> them <HI>cannot</HI> &s;ay, the <HI>Lord</HI> is <HI>my Righteou&s;ne&s;s.</HI>&mdash;O <HI>grey-headed</HI> Sinners, I could <HI>weep</HI> over you<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&mdash;your <HI>grey Hairs,</HI> which ought to be your <HI>Crown,</HI> and in which perhaps <HI>you glory,</HI> is now you<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&punc; <HI>S<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ame.</HI>&mdash;You know not, that the <HI>Lord</HI> is <HI>your</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s.&mdash;Oh, <HI>ha&s;te</HI> then, <HI>ha&s;te</HI> ye, <HI>aged Sinners,</HI> and &s;eek <HI>an Intere&s;t</HI> in <HI>redeeming</HI> Love!&mdash;Alas, you have <HI>one Foot</HI> already in the <HI>Grave</HI>&mdash;Your <HI>Gla&s;s</HI> is ju&s;t <HI>run out</HI>&mdash;Your <HI>Sun</HI> is ju&s;t <HI>going down,</HI> and it will <HI>&s;et</HI> and <HI>leave you</HI> in an <HI>eternal Darkne&s;s,</HI> unle&s;s the <HI>Lord</HI> be <HI>your Righteou&s;ne&s;s!</HI>&mdash;Flee then, Oh <HI>flee</HI> for <HI>your Lives!</HI> Be not <HI>afraid.</HI>&mdash;All Things <HI>are po&s;&s;ible</HI> with <HI>God.</HI> If you <HI>come,</HI> tho' it be at the <HI>eleventh Hour,</HI> Chri&s;t Je&s;us will in <HI>no wi&s;e</HI> ca&s;t you out. Oh, &s;eek then for the <HI>Lord</HI> to be <HI>your</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s, and <HI>be&s;eech</HI> him to <HI>let you</HI> know <HI>how it is</HI> that a Man may be <HI>born again</HI> when he is <HI>old!</HI>&mdash;But I mu&s;t not forget the <HI>Lambs</HI> of the Flock&mdash;To <HI>feed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI> was one of my Lord's <HI>la&s;t</HI> Commands.&mdash;I know he will be <HI>angry</HI> with me, if I <HI>do not tell the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">&punc;</HI> that the <HI>Lord</HI> may be <HI>their</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s; and that <HI>of &s;uch</HI> is the Kingdom of Heaven.&mdash;Come then, <HI>ye little Children,</HI> come to <HI>Chri&s;t;</HI> the <HI>Lord Chri&s;t</HI> &s;hall be <HI>your</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s&punc;&mdash;Do not <HI>think,</HI> that you are <HI>too young</HI> to be <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;Perhaps <HI>many of you</HI> may be <HI>nine</HI> or <HI>ten</HI> Years <HI>old,</HI> and yet <HI>cannot &s;ay,</HI> the <HI>Lord</HI> is <HI>our Righte|ou&s;ne&s;s;</HI> which many <HI>have</HI> &s;aid, tho' <HI>younger</HI> than <HI>you</HI>&mdash;Come then, <HI>while</HI> you are <HI>young</HI>&mdash;Perhaps you may not <HI>live</HI> to be <HI>old</HI>&mdash;Do not <HI>&s;tay</HI> for u<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">her&punc;
<PB N="28" REF="005311_0035_10180ECB8EBAA140">
People&mdash;If your <HI>Fathers</HI> and <HI>Mothers</HI> will not <HI>come</HI> to Chri&s;t, do <HI>you</HI> come <HI>without them.</HI>&mdash;L<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> <HI>Children</HI>&mdash;lead them, and &s;hew <HI>them how the</HI> Lord may be <HI>their</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s.&mdash;Our Lord Je&s;us <HI>loved little Children</HI>&mdash;You are his <HI>Lambs</HI>&mdash;He bids me <HI>feed</HI> you.&mdash;I pray God make you <HI>willing be|time,</HI> to take the <HI>Lord</HI> for <HI>your</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s.</P>
<P>Here then I could <HI>conclude</HI>&mdash;but I mu&s;t not forget the <HI>poor Negroes</HI>&mdash;No, I <HI>mu&s;t not.</HI> Je&s;us Chri&s;t has <HI>died for them,</HI> as well as <HI>others.</HI>&mdash;Nor do I mention <HI>you la&s;t,</HI> becau&s;e I <HI>de&s;pi&s;e your Souls,</HI> but <HI>becau&s;e</HI> I would have what I have to &s;ay, make the <HI>deeper Impre&s;&s;ion</HI> upon your Hearts.&mdash;Oh that you would &s;eek the <HI>Lord</HI> to be <HI>your Righteou&s;ne&s;s!&mdash;</HI> Who knows but he <HI>may be found of you</HI>&mdash;For in <HI>Je&s;us Chri&s;t</HI> there is neither <HI>Male or Female, Bond</HI> or <HI>Free,</HI> even you may be the Children of <HI>God,</HI> if you believe in Je&s;us.&mdash;Did you never read of the <HI>Eunuch</HI> belonging to the Queen of <HI>Cand<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ce!</HI>&mdash;A <HI>Negro</HI> like <HI>your&s;elves.</HI>&mdash;He <HI>believed.</HI>&mdash;The <HI>Lord</HI> was <HI>his</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s. He was <HI>baptized.</HI> Do <HI>you</HI> al&s;o <HI>believe,</HI> and <HI>you</HI> &s;hall be <HI>&s;aved.</HI>&mdash;Chri&s;t Je&s;us is the &s;ame <HI>now,</HI> as He was <HI>Ye&s;terday,</HI> and will wa&s;h <HI>you</HI> in his <HI>own Blood.</HI>&mdash;Go home then, turn the Words of the <HI>Text</HI> into a <HI>Prayer,</HI> and intreat the <HI>Lord</HI> to be <HI>your</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s.&mdash;<HI>Even &s;o,</HI> Come <HI>Lord Je&s;us,</HI> come <HI>quickly,</HI> into <HI>all</HI> our Souls! Amen, <HI>Lord Je&s;us,</HI> Amen and Amen!</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="2" TYPE="sermon">
<PB N="29" REF="005311_0036_10180ED09E7EC340">
<HEAD>SERMON II.</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Seed of the Woman and the Seed of the Serpent.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<BIBL>GENESIS iii. 15.</BIBL>
<Q><HI>And I will put Enmity between thee and the Woman, and between thy Seed and her Seed; it &s;hall brui&s;e thy Head, and thou &s;halt brui&s;e his Heel.</HI></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>WHEN I read to you the&s;e Words, I may addre&s;s you in the Language of the Holy Angels to the Shepherds, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> were watching their Flocks by Night. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> <HI>"hold I bring you glad Tidings of great Joy <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI>&mdash;For this is the fir&s;t Promi&s;e that was <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> of a Saviour to the apo&s;tate Ra<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;We generally look for Chri&s;t only in the New Te&s;tament; but Chri&s;tianity, i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> is very near as old as the Creation.&mdash;It is won|derful to ob&s;erve, how gradually God revealed
<PB N="30" REF="005311_0037_10180ED22A238190">
his Son to Mankind. He began with the Pro|mi&s;e in the Text, and this the Elect lived upon till the Time of <HI>Abraham.</HI>&mdash;To him God made further Di&s;coveries of his eternal Coun&s;el con|cerning Man's Redemption&mdash;Afterwards, at &s;undry Times, and in divers Manners, God &s;poke to the Fathers by the Prophets, till at length the LORD JESUS <HI>him&s;elf was manife&s;t in the Fle&s;h,</HI> and came &amp; tabernacled among&s;t us.</P>
<P>This fir&s;t Promi&s;e mu&s;t certainly be but dark to our fir&s;t Parents, in compari&s;on of that great Light which we enjoy.&mdash;And yet, dark as it was, we may a&s;&s;ure our &s;elves they built upon it their Hopes of everla&s;ting Salvation, and by that Faith were &s;aved.</P>
<P>How they came to &s;tand in need of this Pro|mi&s;e, and what is the Extent and Meaning of it, I intend, God willing, to make the &s;ubject Matter of your pre&s;ent Meditation.</P>
<P>The Fall of Man is written in too legible Characters not to be under&s;tood&mdash;Tho&s;e that deny it, by their denying, prove it.&mdash;The very Heathens confe&s;s'd and bewailed it&mdash;They could &s;ee the Streams of Corruption running through the whole Race of Mankind, but could not trace them to the Fountain-Head.&mdash;Before God gave a Revelation of his Son Man was a Riddle to him&s;elf&mdash;And <HI>Mo&s;es</HI> unfolds more&punc; in this one Chapter (out of which the Text <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> taken) than all Mankind could have been capable of finding out of them&s;elves, tho' they had &s;tudied to all Eternity.</P>
<P><PB N="31" REF="005311_0038_10180ED3B12D33F0">
In the foregoing Chapter, he had given us a full Account, how God &s;poke the World into Being; and e&s;pecially how he formed Man of the Du&s;t of the Earth and breathed into him the Breath of Life, &s;o that he became a living Soul.&mdash;A Council of the Trinity was called concerning the Formation of this lovely Crea|ture.&mdash;The Re&s;ult of that Council was, <HI>Let us make Man in our Image after our Likene&s;s.&mdash;"So God created Man in his own Image, in the Image of God created he him."&mdash;Mo&s;es</HI> remarkably re|peats the Words, that we might take particular. Notice of our divine Original.&mdash;Never was &s;o much expre&s;s'd in &s;o few Words.&mdash;None but a Man in&s;pired could have done &s;o. But it is re|markable, that tho' <HI>Mo&s;es</HI> mentions our being made in the <HI>Image of God,</HI> yet he mentions <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> but <HI>twice,</HI> and that, as it were, in a tran&s;ient Manner, as tho' he would have &s;aid, <Q>Man was made in Honour, God made him upright&punc; <HI>in the Image of God Male and Female created he them.</HI> But Man &s;o &s;oon fell, and became like the Bea&s;ts that peri&s;h, nay, like the Devil him&s;elf, that it is &s;carce worth men|tioning.</Q></P>
<P>How &s;oon Man fell after he was created, i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> not told us, and therefore, to fix any Time, is to be wi&s;e above what is written.&mdash;And, I think&punc; they who &s;uppo&s;e that Man fell the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Day in which he was made, have no &s;ufficient Ground for their Opinion.&mdash;The many Things which are crouded together in the former <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">, the Formation of <HI>Adam's</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> his
<PB N="32" REF="005311_0039_10180ED561432EB8">
giving Names to the Bea&s;ts, and his being put into the Garden which God had planted, I think require a longer Space of Time than a Day to be tran&s;acted in.&mdash;However, all agree in this, "Man &s;tood not long." How long, or how &s;hort a while, I will not take upon me to deter|mine.&mdash;It more concerns us to inquire, how he came to fall from his Stedfa&s;tne&s;s, and what was the Ri&s;e and Progre&s;s of the Temptation which prevailed over him.&mdash;The Account given us in this Chapter concerning it, is very full, and it may do us much Service, under God, to make &s;ome Remarks upon it.</P>
<P><Q><HI>Now the Serpent,</HI> &s;ays the &s;acred Hi&s;torian, <HI>was more &s;ubtle than any Bea&s;t of the Field which the</HI> LORD GOD <HI>had made, and he &s;aid unto the Woman, yea, hath</HI> GOD <HI>&s;aid, ye &s;hall not eat of every Tree of the Garden.</HI></Q></P>
<P>Tho' this was a real Serpent, yet he that &s;poke was no other than the Devil; from hence, perhaps, called the old Serpent, becau&s;e he took Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of the Serpent when he came to be|guile our fir&s;t Parents&mdash;The Devil envied the Happine&s;s of Man, who was made, as &s;ome think, to &s;upply the Place of the fallen Angels&mdash;God made Man upright, and with full Power to &s;tand if he would&mdash;He was ju&s;t, therefore, in &s;uffering him to be tempted&mdash;If he fell, he had no one to blame except him&s;elf&mdash;But how mu&s;t <HI>Satan</HI> effect his Fall?&mdash;He cannot do it by his Power, he attempts it therefore by Policy&mdash;He take<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of a Serpent, which was more <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> all the Bea&s;ts of the Field, which the
<PB N="33" REF="005311_0040_10180EDAD4C36E00">
Lord God had made; &s;o that Men that are full of Subtilty, but have no Piety, are only Ma|chines for the Devil to work upon, ju&s;t as he plea&s;es.</P>
<P><HI>"And he &s;aid unto the Woman."</HI>&mdash;Here is an In&s;tance of his Subtilty&mdash;He &s;ays unto the Wo|man, the weaker Ve&s;&s;el, and when &s;he was alone from her Hu&s;band, and therefore was more liable to be overcome&mdash;<Q><HI>Yea, hath God &s;aid, ye &s;hall not eat of every Tree of the Garden?</HI></Q> The&s;e Words are certainly &s;poken in An&s;wer to &s;omething which the Devil either &s;aw or heard&mdash;In all Probability, the Woman was now near the Tree of Knowledge of Good and Evil. (For we &s;hall find her, by and by, plucking an Apple from it) perhaps &s;he might be looking at, and wondering what there was in that Tree more than the others, that &s;he and her Hu&s;band &s;hould be forbidden to ta&s;te of it&mdash;<HI>Satan</HI> &s;eeing this, and coveting to draw her into a Parley with him, (for if the Devil can per&s;uade us not to re&s;i&s;t, but to commune with him, he hath gained a great Point) he &s;ays, <Q><HI>Yea, hath God &s;aid, ye &s;hall not eat of every Tree in the Gar|den?</HI></Q>&mdash;The fir&s;t Thing he does, is to per|&s;uade her, if po&s;&s;ible, to entertain hard Thoughts of God&mdash;This is his general Way of dealing with God's Children&mdash;<Q>Yea, &s;ays he, hath God &s;aid, ye &s;hall not eat of every Tree of the Garden? What! hath God planted a Garden, and placed you in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of it only to teaze and perplex you? Hath he planted a Garden, and yet forbid you mak|ing
<PB N="34" REF="005311_0041_10180EDC6638E1B0">
U&s;e of any of the Fruits of it at all?</Q> It was impo&s;&s;ible for him to a&s;k a more in&s;naring Que&s;tion, in order to gain his End: For <HI>Eve,</HI> was here &s;eemingly obliged to an&s;wer, and vin|dicate God's Goodne&s;s. And, therefore,&mdash;</P>
<P><HI>Ver.</HI> 2. The Woman &s;aid unto the Serpent, <Q><HI>We may eat of the Fruit of the Trees of the Garden: (Ver. 3.) of the Fruit of the Tree which is in the mid&s;t of the Garden, God hath &s;aid, ye &s;hall not eat of it, neither &s;hall ye touch it&punc; le&s;t ye die.</HI></Q></P>
<P>The former Part of the An&s;wer was good, <Q>We may eat of the Fruit of the Trees of the Garden, God has not forbid us eating of <HI>every</HI> Tree of the Garden. No, we may eat of the Fruit of the Trees in the Garden, (and, it &s;hould &s;eem even of the Tree of Life, which was as a Sacrament to Man in a State of Innocence) there is only one Tree in the Mid&s;t of the Garden, of which God hath &s;aid, Ye &s;hall not eat of it, neither &s;hall ye touch it, <HI>le&s;t ye die.</HI></Q>&mdash;Here &s;he begins to warp, and Sin begins to conceive in her Heart.&mdash;Already &s;he has contracted &s;ome of the Serpent's Poi&s;on, by talking with him, which &s;he ought not to have done at all. For &s;he might ea&s;ily &s;uppo&s;e, that it could be no good Being, that could put &s;uch a Que&s;tion unto her, and in&s;inuate &s;uch di&s;honourable Thoughts of. God&mdash;She &s;hould therefore have fled from him, and not &s;tood to have parley'd with him at all&mdash;Immediately the ill Effects of it appear,&mdash;&s;he begins to &s;often the Divine Threatning,&mdash;
<PB N="35" REF="005311_0042_10180EDE0ED45F18">
God had &s;aid, the <HI>Day thou eate&s;t thereof thou &s;halt &s;urely die;</HI> or, <HI>dying</HI> thou &s;halt <HI>die.</HI>&mdash;But <HI>Eve</HI> &s;ays, ye &s;hall not <HI>eat</HI> of it, neither &s;hall ye <HI>touch</HI> it <HI>le&s;t</HI> ye die.&mdash;We may be a&s;&s;ured we are fallen into, and begin to fall by Tempta|tion, when we begin to think God will not be as good as his Word, in re&s;pect to the Execu|tion of his Threatnings denounced again&s;t Sin.&mdash;<HI>Satan</HI> knew this, and therefore artfully</P>
<P><Q>Said unto the Woman (<HI>ver.</HI> 4.) <HI>Ye &s;hall not &s;urely die,</HI></Q> in an in&s;inuating Manner, <Q>Ye &s;hall not &s;urely die,&mdash;&s;urely, God will not be &s;o cruel as to damn you only for eat|ing an Apple,&mdash;it cannot be.</Q>&mdash;Alas! how many does <HI>Satan</HI> lead Captive at his Will, by flattering them, that they &s;hall not &s;urely die<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">;&mdash;that Hell-Torments will not be eternal,&mdash;that God is all Mercy;&mdash;that he therefore will not puni&s;h a few Years Sin with an Eternity of Mi&s;ery.&mdash;But <HI>Eve</HI> found God as good as his Word, and &s;o will all they that go on in Sin, under a fal&s;e Hope that they &s;hall not &s;urely die.</P>
<P>We may al&s;o under&s;tand the Words &s;poken, po&s;itively, and this is agreeable to what follows,&mdash;You &s;hall not &s;urely die,&mdash;<Q><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> a De|lu&s;ion, a mere Bugbear, to keep you in a &s;ervile Subjection.</Q></P>
<P>For (<HI>Ver.</HI> 4.) "<HI>God doth know, that in the Day-ye eat thereof, then &s;hall your Eyes be opened, and ye &s;hall be as God's, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Good and Evil."</HI></P>
<P>What Child of God can expect to e&s;cape <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&punc; when God him&s;elf was thus &s;landered
<PB N="36" REF="005311_0043_10180EE0AD3184E0">
even in <HI>Paradi&s;e?</HI> Surely the Under&s;tanding of <HI>Eve</HI> mu&s;t have been, in &s;ome Mea&s;ure, blinded, or &s;he would not have &s;uffered the Tempter to &s;peak &s;uch perver&s;e Things.&mdash;In what odious Colours is God here repre&s;ented! <Q>God doth know, that in the Day ye eat thereof, ye &s;hall be a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> God's,</Q> (equal with God.) So that the grand Temptation, was, that they &s;hould be hereafter under no Controul, equal, if not &s;uperior to God, that made them, knowing Good and Evil.&mdash;<HI>Eve</HI> could not tell what <HI>Satan</HI> meant by this; but, to be &s;ure, &s;he under&s;tood it of &s;ome great Privilege which they were to enjoy.&mdash;And thus <HI>Satan</HI> now points out a Way, which &s;eems right to Sinners, but does not tell them the End of that Way is Death.</P>
<P>To give Strength and Force to this Tempta|tion, in all Probability, <HI>Satan,</HI> or the Serpent, at this Time, pluck'd an Apple from the Tree, and eat it before <HI>Eve,</HI>&mdash;by which <HI>Eve</HI> might be induced to think, that the Sagacity and Power of Speech, which the Serpent had above the other Bea&s;ts, mu&s;t be owing, in a great Mea|&s;ure, to his eating that Fruit; and, therefore, if he received &s;o much Improvement, &s;he might al&s;o expect a like Benefit from it. All this, I think, is clear;&mdash;for, otherwi&s;e, I do not &s;ee with what Propriety it could be &s;aid, <Q><HI>When <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Woman &s;aw that it was good for <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI></Q> How could &s;he know it was good for Food, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> le&s;s &s;he had &s;een the Serpent feed upon it?</P>
<P><HI>Satan</HI> now begins to get Ground a pace, Lu&s;t had conceived in her Heart; &s;hortly
<PB N="37" REF="005311_0044_10180EE5A2B7C970">
will bring forth Sin,&mdash;Sin being conceived brings forth Death.&mdash;<HI>Ver.</HI> 6. <Q><HI>And when the Woman &s;aw that the Tree was good for Food, and that it was plea&s;ant to the Eyes, and a Tree to be de&s;ired to make one wi&s;e, &s;he took of the Fruit thereof, and did eat, and gave al&s;o unto her Hu&s;band, and he did eat.</HI></Q></P>
<P>Our Sen&s;es are the landing Ports of our &s;pi|ritual Enemies.&mdash;How needful is that Re&s;olution of holy <HI>Job, I have made a Covenant with mine Eyes.</HI> When <HI>Eve</HI> began to gaze on the forbid|den Fruit with her Eyes, &s;he &s;oon began to long after it with her Heart.&mdash;When &s;he &s;aw that it was good for Food, and plea&s;ant to the Eyes, (here was the Lu&s;t of the Fle&s;h, and Lu&s;t of the Eye) but, above all, a Tree to be de&s;ired to make one wi&s;e, wi&s;er than God would have her be, nay, as wi&s;e as God him&s;elf; &s;he took of the Fruit thereof, and gave al&s;o unto her Hus|band with her, and he did eat&mdash;As &s;oon as <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;he &s;inned her &s;elf, &s;he turned Tempter to her Hu&s;band.&mdash;Its dreadful, when tho&s;e, who &s;hould be Help-meets for each other in the great Work of their Salvation, are only Promoters of each others Damnation&mdash;But thus it is. If we our|&s;elves are good, we &s;hall excite others to Good|ne&s;s; if we do Evil, we &s;hall entice others to do Evil al&s;o.&mdash;There is a clo&s;e Connexion be|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters"> doing and teaching.&mdash;How needful then <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> for all to take Heed that we do not &s;in any Way our&s;elves, le&s;t we &s;hould became Factors or the Devil, and en&s;nare, perhaps, our neare&s;t
<PB N="38" REF="005311_0045_10180EE7D77C8AF0">
and deare&s;t Relatives? <HI>"She gave al&s;o unto her Hu&s;band with her, and he did eat."</HI></P>
<P>Alas! what a Complication of Crimes was there in this one &s;ingle Act of Sin!&mdash;Here <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> an utter Di&s;belief of God's Threatning&mdash;The utmo&s;t Ingratitude to their Maker, who had <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> lately planted this Garden and placed them in it, with &s;uch a glorious and comprehen&s;ive Charter&mdash;Here's the utmo&s;t Neglect of the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> Po&s;terity, who they knew were to &s;tand or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> with them&mdash;Here was the utmo&s;t Pride of Heart&mdash;They wanted to be equal with God&mdash;Here's the utmo&s;t Contempt put upon his Threatning and his Law&mdash;The Devil is credited and obeyed Before him, and all this only to &s;atisfy their &s;en|&s;ual Appetite. Never was a Crime of &s;uch a complicated Nature, committed by any here below&mdash;Nothing but the Devil's Apo&s;tacy and Rebellion could equal it.</P>
<P>And what are the Con&s;equences of their Di&s;|obedience?&mdash;Are their Eyes opened?&mdash;Yes, their Eyes are opened&mdash;But, alas! it is only to &s;ee their own Nakedne&s;s. For, we are told (<HI>Ver.</HI> 7.) <Q><HI>that the Eyes of them both were opened, and they knew that they were naked.</HI></Q>&mdash;Naked of God, naked of every Thing that was holy and good&mdash;and de&s;titute of the Divine Image, which they before enjoyed&mdash;They might <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ghtly, now be termed <HI>Ichab<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">d;</HI> for the Glory of the Lord departed from them&mdash;Oh! how <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ow did the&s;e Sons of the Morning then fall&punc; out o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> God into them&s;elves; from being Partakers <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Divine Nature, into the Nature of the De|vil
<PB N="39" REF="005311_0046_10180EE966269A00">
and the Bea&s;t&mdash;Well, therefore, might they know that they were naked, not only in Body but in Soul.&mdash;</P>
<P>And how do they behave now they are naked?&mdash;Do they <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">y to God for Pardon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;Do they &s;eek to him for a Robe to cover their Naked|ne&s;s?&mdash;No. They were now dead to God, earthly, &s;en&s;ual, devili&s;h&mdash;And, therefore, in &s;tead of applying to God for Mercy, they <HI>&s;ewed,</HI> or <HI>platted Fig-leaves together, and made them&s;elves <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">,</HI> or Things to gird about them. This <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> a lively Repre&s;entation of all natural Men&mdash;We &s;ee that we are naked&mdash;We, in &s;ome Mea&s;ure, confe&s;s it, but, in&s;tead of looking up to God for Succour, we patch up a Righteou&s;ne&s;s of our own (as our fir&s;t Parents platted Fig-leaves to|gether) hoping to cover our Nakedne&s;s by that.&mdash;But our Righteou&s;ne&s;s will not &s;tand the Se|verity of God's Judgment: It will do us no more Service than the Fig-leaves did <HI>Adam</HI> and <HI>Eve</HI>&mdash;that is, none at all.</P>
<P>For (<HI>Ver.</HI> 8.) <Q><HI>They heard the Voice of the Lord God walking in the Trees of the Garden&punc; in the Cool of the Day; and Adam and his Wife</HI> (notwith&s;tanding their Fig-leaves) <HI>hid them&s;elves from the Pre&s;ence of the Lord God, among the Trees of the Garden.</HI></Q></P>
<P>They heard the <HI>Voice</HI> of the Lord God, or the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the Lord God, even the Lord-Je&s;us <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, who is <HI>the Word that was with God, and Word that was God.</HI>&mdash;They heard him walk-in the Trees of the Garden, in the <HI>Cool of Day&punc;</HI>&mdash;A Sea&s;on, perhaps, when <HI>Adam</HI> and
<PB N="40" REF="005311_0047_10180EF040D282A0">
<HI>Eve</HI> u&s;ed to go, in an e&s;pecial Manner, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> offer up an Evening Sacrifice of Prai&s;e and Thank&s;giving&mdash;The <HI>Cool of the Day.</HI> Perhaps, the Sin was committed early in the Morning, or at Noon.&mdash;But God would not come upon them immediately&mdash;He &s;taid till the Cool of the Day. For, if we would effectually repro<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> others, we &s;hould not do it when they are warmed with Pa&s;&s;ion, but wait till the Cool <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Day.&mdash;</P>
<P>But what an Alteration is here!&mdash;In&s;tead<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> rejoicing at the Voice of their Beloved&mdash;in&s;tead of meeting him with open Arms, and enlarge&punc; Hearts, as before, they now hide them&s;elves <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Trees of the Garden&mdash;Alas, what a fooli&s;h Attempt was this?&mdash;Surely, they mu&s;t be na|ked, otherwi&s;e, how could they think of hiding them&s;elves from God?&mdash;Whither could they flee from his Pre&s;ence?&mdash;But, by their F<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ll, they had contracted an Enmity again&s;t God. They now hated, and were afraid to conve<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> with God their Maker.&mdash;And is not this <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Ca&s;e by Nature? A&s;&s;uredly it is. We labour to cover our Nakedne&s;s, with the Fig-leaves o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> our own Righteou&s;ne&s;s&mdash;We hide our &s;elves from God as long as we can, and will not come, and never &s;hould come, did not the Father pre|vent, draw, and &s;weetly con&s;train us, by his Grace, as he here prevented <HI>Adam.</HI></P>
<P>Ver. 9. <Q><HI>And the Lord God called unto Adam and &s;aid unto him, Adam, where art thou?</HI></Q></P>
<P>"The Lord God called unto <HI>Adam"&punc;</HI> (for otherwi&s;e <HI>Adam</HI> would never have called unto
<PB N="41" REF="005311_0048_10180EF1C798D300">
the Lord God) and &s;aid,<Q><HI>Adam, where ar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> thou?</HI>&mdash;How is it, that thou <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not to pay thy Devotions as u&s;ual?</Q>&mdash;Chri&s;tians, remember the Lord keeps an Account when you fail coming to Wor&s;hip&mdash;Whenever there|fore, you are tempted to with-hold your Atten|dance, each of you fancy you heard the Lord God calling unto you, and &s;aying, <Q>O Man, O Woman, where art thou?</Q>&mdash;It may be under&s;tand in another &amp; better Sen&s;e&mdash;<Q><HI>Adam, where art thou?</HI></Q>&mdash;What a Condition is thy poor Soul in?&mdash;This is the fir&s;t Thing the Lord a&s;ks, and convinces a Sinner of, when he pre|vents, and calls him effectually by his Grace&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> al&s;o calls him by Name: For unle&s;s God &s;peaks to us in particular, and we know where we are, how poor, how mi&s;erable, how blind, how naked, we &s;hall never value the Redemption wrought out for us by the Death and Obedience of the dear Lord Je&s;us&mdash;<HI>Adam&punc; where art thou?</HI></P>
<P><HI>Ver.</HI> 1<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">. <Q><HI>And he &s;aid, I heard thy Voice in the Garden, and I was afraid.</HI></Q>&mdash;See what Cowards Sin makes us&mdash;If we knew no Sin, we &s;hould know no Fear <Q><HI>Becau&s;e I was naked, and I hid my&s;elf&mdash;Ver. 11. And he &s;aid, Who told thee that thou wa&s;t naked? Ha&s;t thou eaten of the Tree, whereof I</HI> (thy Ma<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">r and Lawgiver) <HI>commanded th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s, tha<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> thou &s;hould&s;t not eat?</HI></Q>&mdash;</P>
<P>God knew very well that <HI>Adam</HI> was naked, and that he had eaten of the forbidden Fruit.&mdash;But God would know it from <HI>Adam's</HI> own Mouth.&mdash;Thus God knows all our Nece&s;&s;ities
<PB N="42" REF="005311_0049_10180EF35F8F0290">
before we a&s;k, but yet in&s;i&s;ts upon our a&s;king for his Grace, and confe&s;&s;ing our Sins.&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, by &s;uch Acts, we acknowledge our Dependance upon God, take Shame to our &s;elves, and there|by give Glory to his great Name.</P>
<P><HI>Ver.</HI> 12. <Q><HI>And the Man &s;aid, the Woman which thou <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to be with me, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">he gave me of the Tree, and I did eat.</HI></Q></P>
<P>Never was Nature more lively <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">. See what Pride <HI>Adam</HI> contracted by the Fall How unwilling he is to lay the Bl<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">me <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> on, or take Shame to him&s;elf.&mdash;This An&s;wer&punc; full<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> In&s;olence towards God, Enmity again&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Wife, and Di&s;ingenuity in re&s;pect to him&s;elf. For herein he tacitly reflects upon God&mdash;<HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Woman that</HI> THOU <HI>gave&s;t to be with me<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> A<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> much as to &s;ay, <HI>if </HI> THOU <HI>had&s;t not given me</HI> THAT WOMAN, <HI>I had not eaten the forbidden Fruit.</HI>&mdash;Thus when Men &s;in, they <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ay the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> upon their Pa&s;&s;ions; then blame and reflect upon God for giving them tho&s;e Pa&s;&s;ion.&mdash;Their Lan|guage is&mdash;<Q>The Appetites that THOU gave&s;t us, they deceived us, and therefore we <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> again&s;t thee.</Q>&mdash;But, as God, notwith|&s;tanding, puni&s;hed <HI>Adam</HI> for hearkening to the Voice of his Wi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e, &s;o he will puni&s;h th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;e who hearken to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Dictate<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> of their corrupt In<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ations&mdash;For God compels no Man to &s;in. <HI>Adam</HI> might have with&s;tood the Solicitations o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> his Wife, if he would. And &s;o, if we look up to God we &s;hould find Grace to help in the Time of Need&mdash;The Devil and our own Hearts tempt, but they cannot force us to con&s;ent,
<PB N="43" REF="005311_0050_10180EF54A683EE0">
without the Concurrence of our own Wills. So that our Damnation is of our&s;elves, as it will evidently appear at the great Day, notwith|&s;tanding all Men's pre&s;ent impudent Replies again&s;t God&mdash;As <HI>Adam</HI> &s;peaks in&s;olently in re|&s;pect to God, &s;o he &s;peaks with Enmity again&s;t his Wife&mdash;The Woman, or <HI>this</HI> Woman, <HI>&s;he gave me</HI>&mdash;He lays all the Fault upon her, and &s;peaks of her with much Contempt&mdash;He does not &s;ay, my Wife, my dear Wife, but <HI>this Wo|man.</HI>&mdash;For Sin di&s;unites the mo&s;t united Hearts. It is the Bane of holy Fellow&s;hip&mdash;Tho&s;e who have been Companions in Sin here, if they die without Repentance, will both hate &amp;condemn one another hereafter&mdash;All damned Souls are Accu&s;ers of their Brethren&mdash;Thus it is, in &s;ome Degree, on this Side the Grave&mdash;<Q><HI>The Woman whom</HI> THOU <HI>gave&s;t to be with me, &s;he gave me of the Tree, and I did eat.</HI></Q>&mdash;What a di&s;|ingenuous Speech was here!&mdash;He makes u&s;e&punc; of no le&s;s than fifteen Words to excu&s;e him&s;elf, and but one or two (in the Original) to confe&s;s his Fault, if it may be called a Confe&s;&s;ion at all&mdash;<Q><HI>The Woman which thou gave&s;t to be with me, &s;he gave me of the Tree</HI>&mdash;Here are <HI>fifteen</HI> Words&mdash;<HI>and I did eat</HI></Q>&mdash;With what Reluc|tance do the&s;e la&s;t Words come out? How &s;oon are they utter'd? <HI>"And I did <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">."</HI> But thus it is with an unhumbled, unregenerate Heart.&mdash;It will be laying the Fault upon the deare&s;t Friend in the World, nay, upon God him&s;elf, rather than take Shame to it&s;elf&mdash;This Pride we are all &s;ubject to by the Fall, and, till
<PB N="44" REF="005311_0051_10180EF94BB22FB8">
our Hearts are broken, and made contrite by the Spirit of our Lord Je&s;us Chri&s;t, we &s;hall be always charging God fooli&s;hly.&mdash;<HI>Again&s;t</HI> THEE, <HI>and</HI> THEE only, <HI>have I &s;inned, that thou mighte&s;t be ju&s;tified in thy Saying, and clear when thou art judged,</HI> is the Language of none but tho&s;e, who, like <HI>David,</HI> are willing to confe&s;s their Faults, and are truly &s;orry for their Sins.&mdash;This was not the Ca&s;e of <HI>Adam</HI>&mdash;His Heart was not broken; and therefore he lays the Fault of his Di&s;obedi|ence upon his Wife and God, and not upon him&s;elf&mdash;<Q><HI>The Woman which</HI> THOU <HI>gave&s;t to be with me, &s;he gave me of the Tree, and I did eat.</HI></Q>&mdash;</P>
<P><HI>Ver.</HI> 13. <Q><HI>And the Lord God &s;aid, what is this that thou ha&s;t done?"</HI>&mdash;What a wonderful Concern does God expre&s;s in this Expo&s;tulation!&mdash; What a Deluge of M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ry ha&s;t thou bro't upon thy&s;elf, thy Hu&s;band, and thy Po&s;terity? What is this that thou ha&s;t done? Di&s;obey|ed thy God, obeyed the Devil, and ruined they Hu&s;band, for whom I made thee to be an Help-meet!&mdash;What is this that thou ha&s;t done?</Q>&mdash;God would here awaken her to a Sen&s;e of her Crime and Danger, and therefore, as it were, thunders in her Ears. For the Law mu&s;t be preached to &s;elf-righteous Sinners.&mdash;We mu&s;t take Care of healing before we &s;ee Sinners wounded, le<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t we &s;hould &s;ay, <HI>Peace, Peace;</HI> where there's&punc; <HI>no Peace</HI>&mdash;Secure Sinners mu&s;t hear the Thunderings of Mount <HI>Sinai,</HI> before <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> bring them to Mount <HI>Si<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n.</HI>&mdash;They who never preach up the Law, it's to be feared, are un&s;kilful
