<P>I have been the more particular in remarking this Part of their Behaviour, becau&s;e it tends &s;o much to the magnifying of <HI>Free Grace,</HI> and plainly &s;hews us Salvation cometh only from the Lord&mdash;Let us take a &s;hort View of the mi&s;era|ble Circum&s;tances our fir&s;t Parents were now in. They were legally and &s;piritually dead&mdash;Chil|dren of Wrath, and Heirs of Hell&mdash;They had eaten the Fruit, of which God had commanded them, that they &s;hould not eat&mdash;And when ar|raigned before God, notwith&s;tanding their Crime was &s;o complicated, they could not be brought to confe&s;s it&mdash;What Rea&s;on can be given, why Sentence of Death &s;hould not be pronounced again&s;t the Pri&s;oners at the Bar?&mdash;All mu&s;t own they are worthy to die. Nay, how can God, con&s;i&s;tently with his Ju&s;tice, po&s;&s;ibly forgive them&punc;&mdash;He had threaten'd, that the Day wherein they eat of the forbidden Fruit, they &s;hould <HI>&s;urely die</HI>&mdash;And, if he did not execute this Threatning, the Devil might then &s;lander <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Almighty indeed. And yet Mercy cries, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the&s;e Sinners, &s;pare the Work of thine own Hands.&mdash;Behold then Wi&s;dom contrives a Scheme how God may be ju&s;t, and yet be mer|ciful; be faithful to his Threatning, puni&s;h the Offence, &amp; at the &s;ame Time &s;pare the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> An amazing Scene of divine Love here open to our View, which had been from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> in the Heart of God&mdash;Notwith&s;tanding <HI>Adam</HI> &amp; <HI>Eve</HI> were thus unhumbled <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> did not
