Mount, and returned unto the young Men, <HI>Ver.</HI> 19. With what Joy may we imagine he went home, and related all that had pa&s;&s;ed to <HI>Sarah!</HI>&mdash;And above all, with what Triumph is he exulting now in the Paradi&s;e of God, and adoring rich, free, di&s;tingui&s;hing, electing, everla&s;ting Love, which alone made him to differ from the re&s;t of Mankind, and tender him wor|thy of that Title which he will have given him &s;o <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">long as the Sun and the Moon endureth&mdash;<HI>"The Father of the Faithful."</HI></P>
<P>But let us now draw our Eyes from the Crea|ture, and do what <HI>Abraham,</HI> if he was pre&s;ent, would direct to&mdash;I mean, fix them on the Creator, God <HI>ble&s;&s;ed for evermore.</HI></P>
<P>I &s;ee your Hearts affected, I &s;ee your Eyes weep&mdash;(And indeed, who can refrain weeping at the Relation of &s;uch a Story?)&mdash;But, behold! I &s;hew you a My&s;tery, hid under the Sacrifice of&punc; <HI>Abraham'</HI>s only Son, which, unle&s;s your Hearts are hardned, mu&s;t cau&s;e you to weep Tears of Love, and that plentifully too&mdash;I would willingly hope you even prevent me here, and are ready to &s;ay, <Q>It is the Love of God, in giving Je&s;us Chri&s;t to die for our Sins&mdash;Yes, that is it</Q>&mdash;And yet perhaps you find your Hearts, at the mentioning of this, not &s;o much affected&mdash;Let this convince you&punc; that we are all fallen Creatures, and that we do no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> love God o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> Chri&s;t, as we ought to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> if you admire <HI>Abraham</HI> offering <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> how much more ought you to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> and adore the Love of God, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">
