<P>And he, <HI>Ver.</HI> 6. <HI>Trembling and a&s;toni&s;hed&punc; &s;aid, Lord, what wilt thou have me to do?</HI> Tho&s;e who think <HI>Saul</HI> had before a Di&s;covery <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Je&s;us made to his Heart, think that this Que&s;tion is the Re&s;ult of his Faith, and that he now de&s;ires to know, what he &s;hall do out of Gratitude for
<PB N="112" REF="005311_0119_101819C3EF4F0DB0">
what the Lord had done for his Soul&mdash;In th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> this Sen&s;e it may be under&s;tood&mdash;<NOTE N="*" PLACE="foot">See my Sermon on, <HI>What think ye of Chri&s;t?</HI></NOTE> And I have made u&s;e of it as an In&s;tance to prove, that Faith will work by Love&mdash;But perhaps it may be more agreeable to the Context, if we &s;uppo&s;e, that <HI>Saul</HI> had only &s;ome di&s;tant Di&s;covery of Chri&s;t made to him, and not a full A&s;&s;urance of Faith&mdash;For we are told, <HI>he trembling and a&s;to|ni&s;hed,</HI> trembling at the Thoughts of his per&s;e|cuting a <HI>Je&s;us,</HI> and a&s;toni&s;hed at his own Vile|ne&s;s, and the infinite Conde&s;cen&s;ion of this <HI>Je&s;us,</HI> cries out, <HI>Lord, what wilt thou have me do?</HI>&mdash;For Per&s;ons under Soul-Trouble, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ore Conviction, would be glad to do any Thing, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> comply on any Terms, to get Peace with God&mdash;<Q><HI>Ari&s;e,</HI> &s;ays our Lord, <HI>and go into the City, and it &s;hall be told thee what thou &s;halt do</HI></Q>.</P>
<P>And here then will we leave <HI>Saul</HI> awhile, and &s;ee what is become of his Companions&mdash;But what &s;hall we &s;ay? God is a &s;overeign Agent&mdash;His &s;acred Spirit bloweth when and where it li&s;teth&mdash;<HI>He will have Mercy upon whom he will have Mercy. Saul</HI> is taken, but, as far as we know to the contrary, his Fellow-Travellers are le<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t to peri&s;h in their Sins&mdash;For we are told, <HI>Ver.</HI> 7. <HI>That the Men which journyed with him &s;tood indeed &s;peechle&s;s, and hearing a confu&s;ed Voice</HI>&mdash;I &s;ay a <HI>confu&s;ed Voice,</HI> for &s;o the Word &s;ignifies, and mu&s;t be &s;o interpreted, in order to recon<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">le
<PB N="113" REF="005311_0120_101819C782F7A0D8">
it with <HI>Chap.</HI> xxii. <HI>Ver.</HI> 9. where <HI>Saul,</HI> giving an Account of the&s;e Men, tells <HI>Agrippa&mdash;They <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not the Voice of him that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to me</HI>&mdash;They heard a Voice, a confu&s;ed No<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">e, but not the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Voice of him that &s;pake to <HI>Saul,</HI> and therefore remained unconverted&mdash;For what <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> all Ordinances, all even the mo&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Di&s;pen&s;ations of Providence, without <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> to the Soul <HI>in</HI> them&punc;&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> it is now <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Word preached&mdash;Many, like <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI> Companions, are &s;ometimes &s;o &s;truck with the Outgoings of God appearing in the Sanctuary, that they even &s;tand &s;peechle&s;s.&mdash;They hear the Preacher's Voice, but not the Voice of the Son of God, who perhaps at the &s;ame Time is &s;peaking effectually to many other Hear<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&mdash;This I have known often&mdash;And what &s;hall we &s;ay to the&s;e Things! Oh the Depth of the Sovereignty of God! Its pa&s;t finding out&mdash;Lord, I de&s;ire to adore what I cannot <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;o, Father, for &s;o it &s;eemeth good <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Sight.</HI></P>
<P>But to return to <HI>Saul</HI>&mdash;The LORD, <HI>Ver.</HI> 6. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> him <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and <HI>go</HI> into the City&mdash;And we are <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>Ver.</HI> 8. that SAUL <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> from the Earth; and when his <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">he was &s;o over|powered with the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the Light that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> upon them <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> <HI>no Man, but they led him by the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> him into</HI> Dama&s;|cus. That very <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> which was to be the Place of his executing or impri&s;oning the Di&s;ciples of the Lord. <HI>And <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> (<HI>Ver.</HI> 9.) three Days without Sight, and neither <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> eat or drink.</HI>&mdash;But
<PB N="114" REF="005311_0121_101819CA5042FAA8">
who can tell what Horrors of Con&s;cience, what Convul&s;ions of Soul, what <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and pungent Convictions of Sin he under went during the&s;e three long Days&mdash;It was this took away his Ap|petite (For who can eat or drink when under a Sen&s;e of the Wrath of God for Sin?) and being to be greatly employed hereafter, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> mu&s;t be greatly humbled now&mdash;And therefore the Lord leaves him three Days groaning under the Spirit of Bondage, and buffeted no doubt with the fiery Darts of the Devil, that being tempted like unto his Brethren, he might be able here|after to &s;uccour tho&s;e that were tempted.&mdash;Had <HI>Saul</HI> applied to any of the blind Guides of the Jewi&s;h Church under the&s;e Circum&s;tances, they would have &s;aid he was mad or going be&s;ides him&s;elf, as many carnal Teachers and blind Pha|ri&s;ees now deal with, and &s;o more and more di&s;tre&s;s poor Souls labouring under awakening Convictions of their damnable State&mdash;But God often at our fir&s;t Awakenings vi&s;its us with &s;ore Trials, e&s;pecially tho&s;e who are like <HI>Soul</HI> to &s;hine in the Church, and to be u&s;ed as In&s;tru|ments in bringing many Sons to Glory&mdash;Tho&s;e who are to be highly exalted, mu&s;t fir&s;t be deeply humbled.&mdash;And this I &s;peak for the Comfort of &s;uch who may be now groaning under the Spirit of Bondage, and perhaps like <HI>Saul,</HI> can neither eat nor drink, for I have generally ob|&s;erved, that tho&s;e who have had the deepe&s;t Convictions, have afterwards been <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">avoured with the mo&s;t precious Communications&punc; and enjoyed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the divine Pre&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">nce in their
<PB N="115" REF="005311_0122_101819CF2D2AAEE0">
Souls&mdash;This was afterwards remarkably exem|plified in <HI>Saul,</HI> who was now three Days with|out Sight, and neither did eat nor drink.</P>
<P>But will the Lord leave his poor Servant in this Di&s;tre&s;s? No, his Je&s;us (tho' <HI>Saul</HI> per&s;e|cuted him) promi&s;ed (and he will perform) that it <HI>&s;hould be told him what he mu&s;t do&mdash;And there was (Ver.</HI> 10.) <HI>a certain Di&s;ciple at</HI> Dama&s;cus, <HI>named</HI> Ananias, <HI>and unto him &s;aid the Lord in a Vi&s;ion,</HI> Ananias&mdash;<HI>And he &s;aid, Behold I am here, Lord.</HI>&mdash;Oh what a holy Familiarity is there between Je&s;us Chri&s;t and regenerate Souls&mdash;<HI>Ananias</HI> had been u&s;ed to &s;uch Love-Vi&s;its, and therefore knew the Voice of his Beloved&mdash;The Lord &s;ays <HI>Ananias. Ananias</HI> &s;ays, <HI>Behold I am here, Lord</HI>&mdash;Thus it is that Chri&s;t now, as well as formerly, often talks with his Children at &s;undry Times and after divers Manners, as a Man talketh with his Friend&mdash;But what has the Lord to &s;ay to <HI>Ananias?</HI></P>
<P><HI>Ver.</HI> 11. <HI>And the Lord &s;aid unto him, Ari&s;e and go into the Street which is called</HI> STREIGHT, <HI>and inquire in the Hou&s;e of</HI> Judas, <HI>for one called</HI> Saul <HI>of</HI> Tar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">is (<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> here for your Comfort, O Chil|dren of the mo&s;t high God, what Notice Je&s;us Chri&s;t takes of the Street and the Hou&s;e where his own dear Servants lodge) <HI>for Behold, he pray|eth</HI>&mdash;But why is this u&s;her'd in with the Word <HI>Behold!</HI> What, was it &s;uch a Wonder, to hear that <HI>Saul</HI> was praying! Why <HI>Saul</HI> was a <HI>Pha|ri<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">e,</HI> and therefore, no doubt, fa&s;ted and made long Prayers&mdash;And &s;ince we are told that he profited above many of his Equals, I doubt not
<PB N="116" REF="005311_0123_101819D114B4A0F0">
but he was taken notice of for his Gift in Prayer. And yet it &s;eemed before the&s;e three Days <HI>Saul</HI> never prayed in his Life&mdash;And why? Becau&s;e, before the&s;e three Days, he never felt him&s;elf a <HI>condemned</HI> Creature&mdash;He was alive in his own Opinion, becau&s;e without a Knowledge of the &s;piritual Meaning of the Law, he felt not a want of, and therefore before now, cried not after a Je&s;us, and con&s;equently, tho' he might have &s;aid or made a Prayer (as many Phari&s;ees do now a-days) he never prayed a Prayer.&mdash;But now, Behold! he <HI>prayeth indeed</HI>&mdash;And this was urged as one Rea&s;on why he was converted.&mdash;None of God's Children, as one ob&s;erves, come into the World &s;till-born&mdash;Prayer is the very Breath of the new Creature, and therefore if we are Prayerle&s;s we are Chri&s;tle&s;s&mdash;If we never had the Spirit of Supplication, it is a &s;ad Sign that we never had the Spirit of Grace in our Souls; and you may be a&s;&s;ured you never did pray, unle&s;s you have felt your &s;elves damnable Sinners, and the Want of Je&s;us to be your Saviour.&mdash;May the Lord, whom I &s;erve in the Go&s;pel of his dear Son, prick you all to the Heart, and may it be &s;aid of you all as it was of <HI>Saul,</HI> Behold, they pray!</P>
<P>The Lord goes on to encourage <HI>Ananias</HI> to go to <HI>Saul&mdash;For,</HI> &s;ays he <HI>Ver.</HI> 12. <HI>he hath &s;een in a Vi&s;ion a Man named</HI> Ananias, <HI>coming in, and putting his Hand on him, that he might have his Sight.</HI>&mdash;So that though Chri&s;t converted <HI>Saul</HI> immediately by him&s;elf, yet he will carry on the Work thus begun by a Mini&s;ter&mdash;Happy
<PB N="117" REF="005311_0124_101819D40D8939A8">
they who under Soul-Troubles have &s;uch expe|rienced Guides, and as well acquainted with Je&s;us Chri&s;t as <HI>Ananias</HI> was&mdash;You that have &s;uch, Oh! make much of and be thankful for them&mdash;And you that have them not, tru&s;t in God&mdash;He will carry on his own Work without them.</P>
<P>Doubtle&s;s, <HI>Ananias</HI> was a good Man; but &s;hall I commend him for his An&s;wer to our Lord? I commend him not&mdash;For &s;ays he, <HI>Ver.</HI> 13. <HI>Lord, I have heard by many of this Man, how much Evil he hath done to thy Saints at Jeru&s;alem: And here,</HI> Ver. 14. <HI>he hath Authority from the Chief Prie&s;ts to bind all that call upon thy Name.</HI>&mdash;I fear this An&s;wer proceeded from &s;ome Relicks of Self-Righteou&s;ne&s;s, as well as Infidelity, that lay undi&s;covered in the Heart of <HI>Ananias.&mdash;Ari&s;e,</HI> &s;ays our Lord, <HI>and go into the Street which is called</HI> Streight, <HI>and inquire in the Hou&s;e of</HI> Ju|das, <HI>for one called</HI> Saul <HI>of</HI> Tar&s;us; <HI>for behold, be prayeth!</HI>&mdash;One would think this was &s;ufficient to &s;atisfy him&mdash;But &s;ays <HI>Ananias, Lord, I have heard by many of this Man</HI>&mdash;(he &s;eems to &s;peak of him with much Contempt; for even good Men are apt to think too contemptuou&s;ly of tho&s;e who are yet in their Sins) <HI>how much Evil he hath done to thy Saints in</HI> Jeru&s;alem: <HI>And here he hath Authority from the Chief Prie&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s&punc; to bind all that call upon thy Name</HI>&mdash;And what then <HI>Ananias?</HI> Is any Thing too hard for the <HI>Lord&punc;</HI> Who made thee to differ? May not he who con|verted thee, convert him al&s;o? Surely <HI>Ananias</HI> here forgets him&s;elf, or perhaps fears, left this
<PB N="118" REF="005311_0125_101819D701A0B3C8">
Man who had Authority from the Chief Prie&s;ts, to bind all that call upon Chri&s;t's Name, &s;hould bind him al&s;o, if he went unto him&mdash;But the Lord &s;ilences all Objections with a <HI>Go thy Way.</HI> Ver. 15. <HI>For he is a cho&s;en Ve&s;&s;el unto me, to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ear my Name before the Gentiles, and Kings, and the Children of</HI> I&s;rael&mdash;<HI>For I will &s;hew him</HI> (Ver. 16) <HI>how great Things he mu&s;t &s;uffer for my Name's Sake</HI>&mdash;Here God &s;tops his Mouth immediately, by a&s;&s;erting his Sovereignty, and preaching to him the Doctrine of <HI>Election</HI>&mdash;And the frequent Conver&s;ion of notorious Sinners to God, to me is one great Proof, among&s;t a thou&s;and others, of that precious, but too much exploded, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">adly mi&s;repre&s;ented Doctrine of God's <HI>electing Love</HI>&mdash;From whence is it that &s;uch are taken, whil&s;t thou&s;ands not near &s;o vile die &s;en&s;ele&s;s and &s;tupid? All the An&s;wer that can be given is, <HI>They are cho&s;en Ve&s;&s;els&mdash;Go thy Way,</HI> &s;ays God, <HI>for he is a cho&s;en Ve&s;&s;el unto me, to bear my Name before the Gentiles, and Kings, and the Children of</HI> I&s;rael&mdash;<HI>For I will &s;hew him how great Things he mu&s;t &s;uffer for my Name's Sake</HI>&mdash;Ob&s;erve, what a clo&s;e Connection there is between Doing and Suffering for <HI>Chri&s;t</HI>&mdash;If any of my Brethren in the Mini&s;try are pre&s;ent, let them hear what Preferment we mu&s;t expect, if we are called out to work remarkably for God&mdash;Not great Prebendaries or Bi&s;hopricks, but great Sufferings for our Lord's Name Sake&mdash;The&s;e are the Fruits of our Labour; and he that will not contentedly &s;uffer great Things for preaching Chri&s;t, is not worthy of him&mdash;Suffering will be
<PB N="119" REF="005311_0126_101819DA268023E0">
found to be the be&s;t Preferment, when we are called to give an Account of our Mini&s;try at the Great Day.</P>
<P>I do not hear <HI>Ananias</HI> quarrelling with God concerning the Doctrine of <HI>Election.</HI> No: (Oh that all good Men would in this learn of him!) <HI>He went his Way,</HI> (Ver. 17.) <HI>and en|tered into the Hou&s;e; and put his Hands on him, and &s;aid, Brother</HI> Saul&mdash;Ju&s;t now 'twas <HI>this Man&punc;</HI> Now it is <HI>Brother</HI> Saul&mdash;For it's no Matter what a Man has been, if he be now a Chri&s;tian&mdash;The &s;ame &s;hould be our Brother, our Si&s;ter and Mother. God blots out every Convert's Trangre&s;&s;ions, as with a thick Cloud, and &s;o &s;hould we&mdash;The more vile a Man has been, the more &s;hould we love him when believ|ing on Chri&s;t, becau&s;e Chri&s;t will be more glorified on his Behalf&mdash;I doubt not but <HI>Ananias</HI> was won|derfully delighted to hear that &s;o remarkable <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Per&s;ecutor was brought home to God&mdash;I am per|&s;uaded he felt his Soul immediately united to him by Love, and therefore addre&s;&s;es him not with, <HI>Thou Per&s;ecutor, Thou Murderer,</HI> that came&s;t to Butcher me and my Friends, but <HI>Brother</HI> Saul&mdash;'Tis remarkable that the primitive Chri&s;tians much u&s;ed the Word <HI>Brother</HI> and <HI>Brethren</HI>&mdash;I know it's a Term now much in Reproach, but tho&s;e who de&s;pi&s;e it, I believe would be glad to be of our Brotherhood, when they &s;ee us &s;itting at the Right-hand of the Maje&s;ty on High<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">&punc;<HI>Brother</HI> Saul&mdash;<HI>The Lord (even Je&s;us that appeared unto thee in the Way as thou came&s;t) hath &s;ent me, that thou mighte&s;t receive thy Sight, and be filled
<PB N="120" REF="005311_0127_101819DBDD785790">
with the Holy Gho&s;t</HI>&mdash;At this Time me may &s;uppo&s;e, he laid his Hands upon him. See the Con&s;equences.</P>
<P>Ver. 18. <HI>Immediately there &s;ell from his <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> as it had been Scales, and he received Sight forth with,</HI> not only bodily but &s;piritual Sight&mdash;He immerged as it were into a new World&mdash;He &s;aw and felt too, Things unutterable&mdash;He felt a Union of his Soul with God&mdash;He received the Spirit of Adoption&mdash;He could now, with a full A&s;&s;urance of Faith, cry <HI>Abba, Father</HI>&mdash;Now was he filled with the Holy Gho&s;t&mdash;Now was he filled with the <HI>Love of God &s;hed abroa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"></HI> in his Heart&mdash;Now were the Days of his Mourning ended&mdash;Now was Chri&s;t formed in his Soul&mdash;Now he could give Men and Devils the Challenge, knowing that Chri&s;t had ju&s;tified him&punc;&mdash;Now he &s;aw the Excellencies of Chri&s;t&punc; and e&s;teemed him the <HI>faire&s;t among ten Thou&s;and.</HI> You only know how to &s;ympathize with the Apo&s;tle in his Joy, who, after a long Night of Bondage, have been &s;et free by the Spirit, and have received Joy in the Holy Gho&s;t&mdash;May all that are now mourning, as <HI>Saul</HI> was, be com|forted <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> like Manner!</P>
<P>The Scales then are now removed from the Eyes of <HI>Saul'</HI>s Mind, <HI>Ananias</HI> has done that for him under God, he mu&s;t now do another Office, <HI>viz.</HI> baptize him, and &s;o receive him into the vi&s;ible Church of Chri&s;t&mdash;A good Proof <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> of the Nece&s;&s;ity of Bapti&s;m where it may be had&mdash;For I find here, as well as el&s;ewhere, that Bapti&s;m is admini&s;ter'd even to tho&s;e who had
<PB N="121" REF="005311_0128_101819DE090A8F58">
received the Holy Gho&s;t.&mdash;<HI>Saul</HI> was convinced of this, and therefore ar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">e and was baptized&mdash;And now it is Time for him to recruit the out|ward Man, which by three Days Ab&s;tinence and &s;piritual Conflicts, had been much impair|ed&mdash;We are therefore told, (<HI>Ver.</HI> 19.) <HI>when he had received Meat he was &s;trengthened.</HI></P>
<P>But Oh, with what Comfort did the Apo&s;tle <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> eat his Food&punc;&mdash;I am &s;ure it was with Sin|glene&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&punc; I am per&s;uaded al&s;o with Gladne&s;s of Heart&mdash;And why? He <HI>kn<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">w</HI> that he was re|conciled to God&mdash;And for my own Part, did I not know how blind and flinty our Hearts are by Nature, I &s;hould wonder how any one could eat even his common Food with any Satisfacti|on, who has not &s;ome well-grounded Hope of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> being reconciled to God&mdash;Our Lord inti|mates thus much to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;For in his glorious Prayer, after he has taught us to pray for our daily Bread, immediately adds that Petition, <HI>For|give <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> our Tre&s;pa&s;&s;es</HI>&mdash;As tho' our daily Bread would do us no Service, unle&s;s we were &s;en&s;ible of having the Forgivene&s;s of our Sins.</P>
<P>To proceed: <HI>Saul</HI> hath now received Meat, and is &s;trengthened. And whither will he go now? To &s;ee the Brethren&mdash;<HI>Then was</HI> Saul <HI>certain Days with the Di&s;ciples that were at</HI> Da|ma&s;cus&mdash;For i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> we know, and love Chri&s;t&punc; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hall al&s;o love, and de&s;ire to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e acquainted with the Brethren of Chri&s;t&mdash;We may generally know a Man by his Company. And tho' all are not Saints that a&s;&s;ociate with Saints (for <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ares will be always &s;pringing up among&s;t the
<PB N="122" REF="005311_0129_101819E0AD31C748">
Wheat till the Time of Harve&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> we <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> keep Company, but are &s;hy and a&s;hamed of the de&s;pi&s;ed Children of God, it's a certain <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> we have not yet experimentally learnt Je&s;us, or receiv'd him into our Hearts&mdash;My dear Friend&mdash;Be not deceived&mdash;If we are Friends to the Bridegroom, we &s;hall be Friends to the Children of the Bridegroom&mdash;<HI>Soul,</HI> as &s;oon as he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> filled with the Holy Gho&s;t, <HI>was certain Day with the Di&s;ciples that were at</HI> Dama&s;cus.</P>
<P>But who can tell what Joy the&s;e Di&s;ciples felt when <HI>Saul</HI> came among&s;t them! I &s;uppo&s;e holy <HI>Ananias</HI> introduced him&mdash;Methinks I &s;ee the once pre&s;ecuting Zealot, when they came to &s;alute him with a holy Ki&s;s, throwing him&s;elf upon each of their Necks, weep<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">g over them with Floods of Tears, and &s;aying, <Q>O my Bro|ther, O my Si&s;ter, Can you forgive me&punc; Can you give &s;uch a Wretch as I the Right-hand of Fellow&s;hip, who intended to drag you behind me bound unto <HI>Jeru&s;alem</HI></Q> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s I &s;ay we may &s;uppo&s;e <HI>Saul</HI> addre&s;&s;ed him|&s;elf to his n<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">w Fellow-Di&s;ciples, and I doubt not but they were as ready to forgive and forget as <HI>Ananias</HI> was, and &s;aluted him with the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> learin<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&punc; Title of <HI>Brother Saul</HI>&mdash;Lovely was this Meeting, &s;o lovely, that it &s;eemed <HI>Saul</HI> conti|nued certain Days with them, to communicate Experiences, and to learn the Way of God more per<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ectly, to pray for a Ble&s;&s;ing on his <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Mini&s;try, and to prai&s;e Chri&s;t Je&s;us for what he had done for their Souls&mdash;<HI>Saul</HI> perhaps had <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">at certain Years at the Feet of <HI>Gam<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">li<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">l,</HI> but un|doubtedly
<PB N="123" REF="005311_0130_101819E6DA8250E0">
learnt more there certain Days, than <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> had learnt before in all his Life&mdash;It plea&s;es <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to think how th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> great Scholar is transform'd <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the renewing of his Mind, what a mighty Change was here&punc;&mdash;That &s;o great a Man as <HI>Saul</HI> was, both as to his Station in Life, and in|ternal Qualifications, and &s;uch a bitter Enemy <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Chri&s;tians; for him I &s;ay, to go and be <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Days with the People of THIS <HI>mad</HI> WAY, and to &s;it quietly, and be taught of un|le<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ned and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">literate Men, as many of the&s;e Di&s;ciples we may be &s;ure were&punc; What a &s;ub|&s;tantial Proof was this of the Reality of his Con|ver&s;ion?</P>
<P>What a Hurry and Confu&s;ion may we &s;uppo&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> the Chief Prie&s;ts were in! Now I warrant they were ready to cry out, What is <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e al&s;o deceived? As for the common People, who knew not the Law, and are accur&s;ed, for them to be carried away, is no &s;uch Wonder&mdash;But for a Man bred up at the F<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">et of <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">,</HI> for &s;uch a Scholar, &s;uch an Enemy to their Cau&s;e as <HI>Saul,</HI> for him to be led away with a Company f<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">ly, decei|ved Men and Women, &s;urely it's impo&s;&s;ible&punc; We cannot believe it&punc;But <HI>Saul</HI> &s;oon convin|ces them of the Rea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">y of his becoming a Fool for Chri&s;t's Sake&mdash;For &s;tr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ightway (<HI>Ver.</HI> 20.) in&s;tead of going to deliver the Letters from the High Prie&s;ts, as they expected, in order to bring the Di&s;ciples that were at <HI>Dama&s;cus</HI> bound to <HI>Jeru&s;alem, He preached Chri&s;t in the Synagogues, that he is the Son of God</HI>&mdash;This was another Proof of his being converted&mdash;He not only
<PB N="124" REF="005311_0131_101819E8C89A8F78">
conver&s;ed with Chri&s;tians in private, but he preached Chri&s;t publickly in the Synagogues E&s;pecially he in&s;i&s;ted on the Divinity of our Lord, proving, notwith&s;tanding his Humiliation, that he was really the Son of God.</P>
<P>But why did <HI>Saul</HI> preach Chri&s;t thus? Be|cau&s;e he had felt the Power of Chri&s;t upon his own Soul&mdash;And here's the Rea&s;on why Chri&s;t is &s;o &s;eldom preached, and his Divinity &s;o &s;lightly in&s;i&s;ted on in our Synagogues, 'tis becau&s;e the Generality of tho&s;e that pretend to preach him, never felt a &s;aving Work of Conver&s;ion upon their own Souls&mdash;How can they preach, unle&s;s they are fir&s;t taught of, and then &s;ent by God? <HI>Saul</HI> did not preach Chri&s;t be|fore he knew him, no more &s;hould any one el&s;e.&mdash;An unconverted Mini&s;ter, tho' he could &s;peak with the Tongues of Men and Angels, will be but as a &s;ounding Bra&s;s and tinkling Cymbal to tho&s;e who&s;e Sen&s;es are exerci&s;ed to di&s;cern &s;piri|tual Things&mdash;Mini&s;ters that are unconverted, may talk and declaim of Chri&s;t, and prove from Books that he is the Son of God, but they can|not preach with the Demon&s;tration of the Spirit and with Power, unle&s;s they preach from Expe|rience, and have had a Proof of his Divinity, by a Work of Grace wrought upon their own Souls&mdash;God forgive tho&s;e, who lay Hands on an unconverted Man, knowing that he is &s;uch&mdash;I would not do it for a thou&s;and Worlds&mdash;Lord Je&s;us keep thy own faithful Servants pure, and let them not be then Partakers of other Men's Sins.</P>
<P><PB N="125" REF="005311_0132_101819EA63D314E0">
Such an In&s;tance as <HI>Saul'</HI>s Conver&s;ion was, we may be a&s;&s;ured mu&s;t make a great deal of Noi&s;e, and therefore no Wonder we are told, <HI>Ver.</HI> 21. <HI>But all that heard him were amazed, and &s;aid, Is not this <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e that de&s;troyed them which cal|led on his Name in</HI> Jeru&s;alem, <HI>and came hither for that Intent, that he might bring them bound to the Chief Prie&s;ts?</HI></P>
<P>And thus it will be with all that appear pub|lickly for Je&s;us Chri&s;t; and it's as impo&s;&s;ible for a true Chri&s;tian to be hid, as a City built upon a Hill&mdash;Brethren, if you are faithful to, you mu&s;t be reproached, and have Remarks made on you for Chri&s;t; e&s;pecially if you have been remarkably wicked before your Conver|&s;ion. What, (will your Friends &s;ay) is not this he, or &s;he, who a little while ago would run to as great Exce&s;s of Riot and Vanity as the wor&s;t of us all? What has turned your Brain? Or if you have been clo&s;e, fal&s;e, formal Hypocrites as <HI>Saul</HI> was, they will wonder that <HI>you</HI> &s;hould be &s;o deceived, as to think you were not in a &s;afe State before&mdash;As, no doubt, Num|bers were &s;urprized to hear <HI>Saul,</HI> who was touching the Law blamele&s;s, affirm that he wa<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> in a damnable Condition, (as in all Probability he did) a few Days ago.</P>
<P>Brethren, you mu&s;t expect to meet with many &s;uch Difficulties as the&s;e&mdash;the Scourge of the Tongue is generally the fir&s;t Cro&s;s we are called to bear for the Sake of Chri&s;t&mdash;Let not therefore this move you&mdash;It did not intimidate, no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">, it rather encouraged <HI>Saul.</HI></P>
<P><PB N="126" REF="005311_0133_101819F156C60078">
<HI>But</HI> SAUL, &s;ays the Text, <HI>increa&s;ed the more in Strength, and confounded the Jews which dwelt at</HI> Dama&s;cus, <HI>proving that this is very Chri&s;t.</HI>&mdash;Oppo&s;ition never yet did, nor ever will hurt a &s;incere Convert&mdash;Nothing like Oppo&s;ition to make the Man of God perfect&mdash;None but a Hireling, who careth not for the Sheep, will be affrighted at the Approach or Barking of Wolves&mdash;Chri&s;t's Mini&s;ters are as bold as Lions&mdash;It is not for &s;uch Men as they to flee.</P>
<P>And therefore (that I may draw towards a Conclu&s;ion) let the Mini&s;ters and Di&s;ciples of Chri&s;t, learn from <HI>Saul,</HI> not to fear Men or their Revilings, but, like him, increa&s;e in Strength, the more wicked Men endeavour to weaken their Hands.&mdash;We cannot be Chri&s;tians without being oppo&s;ed&mdash;No&mdash;Di&s;ciples in general mu&s;t &s;uffer&mdash;Mini&s;ters in particular mu&s;t &s;uffer great Things&mdash;But let not this move any of us from our Stedfa&s;tne&s;s in the Go&s;pel&mdash;He that &s;tood by and &s;trengthned <HI>Saul,</HI> will al&s;o &s;tand by and &s;trengthen us. He is a God, mighty to &s;ave all that put their Tru&s;t in him&mdash;If we look up with an Eye of Faith, we, as well as the fir&s;t Martyr St. <HI>Stephen,</HI> may &s;ee Je&s;us &s;tanding at the right Hand of God, ready to a&s;&s;i&s;t and pro|tect us&mdash;Tho' the Lord's Seat is in Heaven, yet he has Re&s;pect to his Saints in an e&s;pecial Man|ner when &s;uffering here on Earth&mdash;Then the Spirit of Chri&s;t and of Glory re&s;ts upon, their Souls. And, if I may &s;peak my own Experi|ence, <Q>I never enjoy more rich Communica|tions from God, than when de&s;pi&s;ed and re|jected
<PB N="127" REF="005311_0134_101819F2E84D8CF8">
of Men for the Sake of Je&s;us Chri&s;t.</Q> However little they may de&s;ign it, my Enemies are my greate&s;t Friends&mdash;What I mo&s;t fear is a Calm; but the Enmity which is in the Hearts of natural Men again&s;t Chri&s;t, will not &s;uffer them to be quiet long&mdash;No. As I hope the Work of God will increa&s;e, &s;o the Rage of Men and Devils will increa&s;e al&s;o&mdash;Let us put on therefore the whole Armour of God&mdash;Oh! let us not fear the Face of Men&mdash;Let us fear him only, who can de&s;troy both Body and Soul in Hell&mdash;I &s;ay unto you, let us fear him alone&mdash;You &s;ee how &s;oon God can &s;top the Fury of his Enemies&mdash;You have ju&s;t now heard of a proud, powerful Zealot &s;top'd in his full Career &s;truck down to the Earth with a Light from Heaven, converted by the Almighty Power of efficacious Grace, and thereupon zealou&s;ly promoting, nay re&s;olutely &s;uffering for the Faith which once with Threatnings &amp; Slaughters he endeavour'd to de&s;troy&mdash;Let this teach us to pity and pray for our Lord's mo&s;t inveterate Enemies&mdash;Who knows, but in An&s;wer thereunto, our Lord may give them Repentance unto Life? Mo&s;t think, that Chri&s;t had Re&s;pect to <HI>Stephen'</HI>s Prayer, when he converted <HI>Saul</HI>&mdash;Perhaps for this Rea|&s;on God &s;uffers his Adver&s;aries to go on, that his Goodne&s;s and Power may &s;hine more bright in their Conver&s;ion&mdash;But let no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> the Per&s;ecu|tors of Chri&s;t take Encouragement from this to continue in their Oppo&s;ition&mdash;Remember, tho' <HI>Saul</HI> was converted, yet the High Prie&s;t and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Companions were left dead in Tre&s;pa&s;&s;es
<PB N="128" REF="005311_0135_101819F62C720570">
and Sins. And if this &s;hould be your Ca&s;e, you will of all Men be mo&s;t mi&s;erable&mdash;For Per&s;e|cutors have the lowe&s;t Place in Hell. <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>Saul</HI> was &s;truck to the Earth by a Light from Heaven, how will you be able to &s;tand before Je&s;us Chri&s;t, when he comes in terrible Maje&s;ty to take Vengeance on all tho&s;e who have per&s;e|cuted his Go&s;pel?&mdash;Then the Que&s;tion, <HI>Why per&s;ecute&s;t thou me?</HI> will cut you through and through&mdash;The &s;ecret Enmity of your Heart &s;hall then be detected before Men and Angels, and you &s;hall be doomed to dwell in the Black|ne&s;s of Darkne&s;s for evermore&mdash;Ki&s;s the Son therefore, le&s;t he be angry&mdash;For even you may yet find Mercy, if you believe on the Son of God&mdash;Tho' you per&s;ecute him, yet he will be your Je&s;us&mdash;I cannot de&s;pair of any of you, when I find a <HI>Saul</HI> among the Di&s;ciples at <HI>Da|ma&s;cus</HI>&mdash;What tho' your Sins are as Scarlet, the Blood of Chri&s;t &s;hall wa&s;h them as white as Snow&mdash;Having much to be forgiven, de&s;pair not, only beelieve, and like <HI>Saul,</HI> of whom I have now been &s;peaking, love much&mdash;He count|ed him&s;elf the chiefe&s;t Sinner of all, and there|fore laboured more abundantly than all. Who is there among you fearing the Lord? Who&s;e Hearts hath the Lord now opened to hearken to the Voice of his poor unworthy Servant?&mdash;Surely the Lord will not let me preach in vain&mdash;Who is the happy Soul that is this Day to be wa&s;hed in the Blood of the Lamb? Will no poor Sinner take Encouragement from <HI>Saul</HI> to come to Je&s;us Chri&s;t? You are all thronging
<PB N="129" REF="005311_0136_101819F820C46998">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">nd about, but which of you will touch the Lord Je&s;us&punc; What a Comfort will it be to <HI>Saul,</HI> and and to your own Souls, when you meet him in Heaven, to tell him, that hea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ing of his, was a Means, under God, of your Con|ver&s;ion. Doubtle&s;s, it was written for the En|couragement of all poor returning Sinners&mdash;He him&s;elf tells us &s;o, for in me, &s;ays he, <HI>God &s;hewed all Long-&s;uffering, that I might be an Example <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> them that &s;hould hereafter believe</HI>&mdash;Was <HI>Saul</HI> here him&s;elf he would tell you &s;o&mdash;Indeed he would; but being dead, by this Account of his Conver|&s;ion, he yet &s;peaketh&mdash;Oh, that God may &s;peak by it to your Hearts! Oh, that the Arrows of God might this Day &s;tick fa&s;t in your Souls, and you were made to cry out&mdash;<HI>Who art thou Lord?</HI> Are there any &s;uch among you? Me|thinks I feel &s;omething of what this <HI>Saul</HI> fel<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> when he &s;aid, <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> vail in Birth again for you, till Chri&s;t be formed again in your Hearts</HI>&mdash;O come, come away to Je&s;us, on whom <HI>Saul</HI> believed, and then I care not if the High Prie&s;ts i&s;&s;ue out ne|ver &s;o many Writs of Indictments, or injuriou&s;ly drag me to a Pri&s;on.&mdash;The Thoughts of being in&s;trumental in &s;aving you, will make me &s;ing Prai&s;es even at Midnight&mdash;And I know you will be my Joy and Crown of rejoicing, when I am delivered from this earthly Pri&s;on, and meet you in the Kingdom of God hereafter.</P>
<P><HI>Now to God,</HI> &amp;c.</P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="6" TYPE="sermon">
<PB N="130" REF="005311_0137_101819FB06F0C390">
<HEAD>SERMON VI.</HEAD>
<HEAD>CHRIST, the Believer's Wi&s;dom, Righteou&s;ne&s;s, Sanctification, and Redemption.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<BIBL>1 COR. i. 30.</BIBL>
<Q><HI>But of him are ye in Chri&s;t Je&s;us, who of God is made unto us, Wi&s;dom, Righteou&s;|ne&s;s, Sanctification, and Redemption</HI></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>OF all the Ver&s;es in the Book of God, this which I have now read to you is, I believe, one of the mo&s;t comprehen|&s;ive&mdash;What glad Tidings does it bring to Believers! What precious Privileges are they herein inve&s;ted with! How are they her<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> led to the Fountain of them all, I mean the Love, the everla&s;ting Love of God the Father&mdash;Of whom are you in Chri&s;t Je&s;us, <HI>who of God is made unto us, Wi&s;dom, Righteou&s;ne&s;s, Sanctifi|cation, and Redemption.</HI></P>
<P>Without referring you at pre&s;ent to the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> text, I &s;hall from the&s;e Words,</P>
<P><PB N="131" REF="005311_0138_101819FE91734CE8">
<HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI> Point out to you the Fountain from <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> all th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;e Ble&s;&s;ing <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, which the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> partake of in Je&s;us Chri&s;t&mdash;<HI>Who of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> is made unto to</HI>&mdash;</P>
<P><HI>Secondly,</HI> I &s;hall con&s;ider what tho&s;e Ble&s;&s;ings <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>viz. Wi&s;dom, Righteou&s;ne&s;s, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">anctification, and Redemption.</HI></P>
<P>And, <HI>Fir&s;t,</HI> I would point out to you, the Foun|tain from which all tho&s;e Ble&s;&s;ings flow, which the Elect of God partake of in Je&s;us&mdash;<HI>Who of God is made unto us,</HI> i. e. God the Father, for <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e it is that is &s;poken of here&mdash;Not as tho' Je&s;us Chri&s;t was not God as well as he&mdash;But God the Father is the Fountain of the Deity, and if we con&s;ider Je&s;us Chri&s;t acting as Mediator, God <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Father is greater than He&mdash;There was an <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ternal Contract between the Father and the Son&mdash;<HI>I have ma<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e,</HI> &s;ays God, <HI>a Covenant with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Cho&s;en, and I have &s;worn unto</HI> David <HI>my Ser|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">nt,</HI> which <HI>David</HI> was a Type of Chri&s;t, with whom the Father made a Covenant, that if <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> would obey and &s;uffer, and make him&s;elf a Sa|crifi<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> for Sin, he &s;hould <HI>&s;ee his Seed, he &s;hould <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> his Day<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">, and the Plea&s;ure of the Lord &s;hould <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in his Hands</HI>&mdash;This Compact our Lord Je&s;us to in that glorious Prayer recorded in the 17th Chapter of St. <HI>John;</HI> and therefore <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">he prays for, or rather demands with a full <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> that were given to him by the Father&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> he, <HI>I will that they al&s;o whom th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> me, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e with me where I am</HI>&mdash;For <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Rea&s;on the Apo&s;tle breaks out into prai&s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> even the Father of our Lord Je&s;us <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">
<PB N="132" REF="005311_0139_10181A002277DE28">
F<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">r he lov<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">d <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> with an everla&s;ting I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> expre&s;&s;es it, <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> of the World</HI>&mdash;And therefore, to &s;hew <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to what <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> were beholden for their <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> our Lord, in the 25th of St. <HI>Matthew, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI> &s;ent <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">, <HI>Come ye ble&s;&s;ed <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> the King <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> prepared <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> from the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> of the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI>&mdash;And <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Reply <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ther of <HI>Ze<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">edee'</HI>s Children, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ays, <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> is not mine to give, but it &s;hall be <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> them, for whom it is prepared of the Father</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> The Apo&s;tle therefore, when here &s;peaking <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Chri&s;tian<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> Privileges, le<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t they &s;hould &s;a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">|fice to their own Drag, or t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ink their Salva<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters"> w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> owing to their own Faithfulne&s;s, or I<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">|provement of their own Free-will, reminds <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to look back on the everla&s;ting Love of God the Father&mdash;<HI>Who of God is made unto us,</HI> &amp;c.</P>
<P>Would to God this Point of Doctrine <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> more and People were more <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> <HI>of Redemption</HI> between the Fa|ther <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Son, we &s;hould then not have &s;o much di&s;puting again&s;t the Doctrine of Election, or hea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> condemned <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">even by good Men) as a Doctrine of Devils&mdash;For my own Part, I can|no<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> &s;ee how true Humblene&s;s of Mind can be attained without a Knowledge of it&mdash;And tho<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> I will not &s;ay, that every one who denies Elec|tion is a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ad Man, yet I will &s;ay, with <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Sweet Singer, Mr. <HI>Trail,</HI> it is a very bad <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Such a one, whoever he be, I think <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> know <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">&mdash;For if we deny Electio<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> mu&s;t &s;ay&punc; what we will) partly at lea&s;t, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">
<PB N="133" REF="005311_0140_10181A020D69DA68">
our&s;elves for &s;uffering Chri&s;t to redeem and &s;ave us&mdash;But our Redemption is &s;o ordered, that no Fle&s;h &s;hould glory in the Divine Pre&s;ence&mdash;And hence it is that the Pride of Man oppo&s;es this Doctrine, becau&s;e according to this Doc|trine, and no other, <HI>he that glories, mu&s;t glory only in the Lord</HI>&mdash;But what &s;hall I &s;ay? Election is a My&s;tery that &s;hines with &s;uch re&s;plendent Brightne&s;s, that, to make u&s;e of the Words of one, who has drank deeply of Electing Love, it dazzles the weak Eyes even of &s;ome of God's dear Children&mdash;However, tho' they know it not, all the Ble&s;&s;ings they receive, all the Privi|ledges they do or will enjoy, thro' Je&s;us Chri&s;t&punc; flow from the everla&s;ting Love of God the Fa|ther&mdash;<HI>But of him are you in Chri&s;t Je&s;us, who of God is made unto us, Wi&s;dom, Righteou&s;ne&s;s, Sanctification, and Redemption.</HI></P>
<P>What the&s;e Ble&s;&s;ings are, which are hope through Chri&s;t made over to the Elect, I come in the next Place to con&s;ider.</P>
<P>And, <HI>Fir&s;t,</HI> Chri&s;t is made to them <HI>Wi&s;dom&punc;</HI> But wherein does <HI>true Wi&s;dom</HI> con&s;i&s;t? <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Was I to a&s;k &s;ome of you, perhaps you would &s;ay, in indulging the Lu&s;t of the Fle&s;h, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to your Souls, Eat, Drink, and be me<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">y&mdash;But <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">his i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> only the Wi&s;dom of Brutes&mdash;They have as good a Gu<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t and Reli&s;h for <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> P<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ea&s;ures&punc; the great<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">t <HI>Epicure</HI> on the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;Others&punc; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> tell me <HI>true Wi&s;dom</HI> con&s;i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ed in adding <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Hou&s;e, and Field to Field, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> their own Names&mdash;But this <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> <HI>Wi&s;dom</HI>&mdash;For Riches often take them|&s;elves
<PB N="134" REF="005311_0141_10181A06996724B0">
Wings, and fly away, like an Eagle to|wards Heaven&mdash;Even <HI>Wi&s;dom it&s;elf</HI> a&s;&s;ures us, <HI>that a Man's Life doth not con&s;i&s;t in the Abundance of the Things which he po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es</HI>&mdash;Vanity, Vanity, all the&s;e Things are Vanity&mdash;For if Riches leave not the Owner, the Owners mu&s;t &s;oon leave them&mdash;<HI>For rich Men mu&s;t al&s;o die, and leave their Riches for others.</HI> Their Riches cannot procure them a Redemption from the Grave, whither we are all ha&s;tening apace&mdash;But perhaps you de&s;pi&s;e Riches and Plea&s;ure, and therefore place Wi&s;dom in the Knowledge of Books&mdash;But it is po&s;&s;ible for you to tell the Numbers of the Stars, and call them all by their Names, and yet <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e mere Fools&mdash;Learned Men are not always wi&s;e&mdash;Nay, our common Learning, &s;o much cried up, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Men only &s;o many accompli&s;hed Fools&mdash;To keep you therefore no longer in Su&s;pence, and withal to humble you, I will &s;end you to an Heathen to School, to learn what <HI>true Wi&s;dom</HI> is&mdash;<HI>"Know thy&s;elf,"</HI> was a Saying of one of the wi&s;e Men of <HI>Greece</HI>&mdash;This is certainly <HI>true Wi&s;dom,</HI> and this is that Wi&s;dom &s;poken of in the Text, and which Je&s;us Chri&s;t is made to all Elect Sinners&mdash;They are made to know them|&s;elves; &s;o as not to think more highly of them|&s;elves than they ought to think&mdash;Before they were Darkne&s;s, now they are Light in the Lord, and in that Light they &s;ee their own Darkne&s;s&mdash;They now bewail that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> by Nature, dead in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Sons and Heirs of Hell, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Wrath&mdash;They now &s;ee that all <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">
<PB N="135" REF="005311_0142_10181A0B8F3A50C0">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> are but as filthy Rags, that there is no Health in their Souls, that they are poor and mi&s;erable, blind and naked, and that there is no Name given under Heaven, whereby they can <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ave<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">, but that of Je&s;us Chri&s;t&mdash;They &s;ee the Nece&s;&s;ity of clo&s;ing with a Saviour, and the Wi&s;dom of God in appointing him to be a Savi|our&mdash;They are al&s;o made willing to accept of Salvation upon our Lord's own Terms, and to receive him as their All in All&mdash;Thus Chri&s;t is made to them <HI>Wi&s;dom.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Secondly,</HI> Righteou&s;ne&s;s&mdash;<HI>Who of God is made unto us, Wi&s;dom, Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI>&mdash;i. e. Chri&s;t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <HI>whole per&s;onal Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI> is made over to&punc; and accounted theirs&mdash;Being enabled to lay hold on Chri&s;t by Faith, God the Father blots out their Tran&s;gre&s;&s;ions, as with a thick Cloud, their Sins, their Iniquities, he remembers no more&mdash;They are made the Righteou&s;ne&s;s of God in Chri&s;t Je&s;us, who is the End of the Law for Righteou&s;ne&s;s to every one that believeth&mdash;In one Sen&s;e, now God <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ees no Sin in them&mdash;The whole Covenant of Works is fulfilled <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> them&mdash;They are actually ju&s;tified, acquir<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> and looked upon <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Righteous in the Sight of God&mdash;They are perfectly accepted in the Be|loved&mdash;They are compleat in him&mdash;The flaming Sword of God's Wrath, which before moved every Way, is now removed, and fr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e&punc; Acce&s;s given to the Tree of Life&mdash;They are enabled now to reach out the Arm of Faith, and pluck and live for evermore&mdash;Hence it is that the Apo&s;tle, under a Sen&s;e of this&punc; ble&s;&s;ed
<PB N="136" REF="005311_0143_10181A0D1F8E52C8">
Privilege, breaks out into this triumphant <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">|guage&mdash;<HI>It is Chri&s;t that ju&s;tified, who <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> condemns me?</HI> Does Sin condemn? Chri&s;t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> Righteou&s;ne&s;s delivers Believers from the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of it&mdash;Chri&s;t is their <HI>Je&s;us,</HI> their <HI>Saviour.</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> is become a Pr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">pitiation for their Sins&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> therefore &s;hall lay any thing to the Charge <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> God's Elect? Does the Law condemn?&mdash;By having Chri&s;t's Righteou&s;ne&s;s imputed to them, they are dead to the Law, as a Covenant <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Works. Chri&s;t has fulfilled it for them, and in their Stead&mdash;Does Death threaten them? They need not <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ear&mdash;The Sting of Death is Sin, the Strength of Sin is the Law; but God <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> given them Victory, by imputing to them the Righ|teou&s;ne&s;s of the Lord Je&s;us.</P>
<P>And what a Privilege is here! Well might the Angels at the Birth of Chri&s;t &s;ay to the humble Shepherds, <HI>"Behold I bring you glad <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Trdings of great Joy."</HI> For unto you that believe in Chri&s;t, <HI>a Saviour is born.</HI> And well may they rejoice at the Conver&s;ion of poor Sin+ners <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> the Lord is their Righteou&s;ne&s;s&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Peace with God, through Faith in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Blood, and &s;hall never enter into Con|demnation&mdash;Oh, Believer<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> (for this Di&s;cour&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> in a &s;pecial Manner for you) Li<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">t <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> your Heads&mdash;<HI>Rejoice in the Lord always, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> I &s;ay rejoice</HI>&mdash;Chri&s;t is made to you of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ighteou&s;ne&s;s&punc; What then &s;hould you <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> are made the Righteou&s;ne&s;s of God <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> may be called <HI>The Lord our Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI>&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> what then &s;hould you be <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">? What &s;hall
<PB N="137" REF="005311_0144_10181A0EB87118C0">
&s;eparate you henceforward from the Love of Chri&s;t? Shall Tribulation, or Di&s;tre&s;s, or Per|&s;ecution, or Famine, or Nakedne&s;s, or Peril, or Sword? No, I am per&s;waded neither Death, nor Life, nor Angels, nor Principalities, nor Powers, nor Things pre&s;ent, nor Things to come, nor Height, nor Depth, nor any other Creature, &s;hall be able to &s;eparate you from the Love of God, which is in Chri&s;t Je&s;us our Lord, who of God is made unto you <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s</HI>&mdash;</P>
<P>This is a glorious Privilege&mdash;But this is only the Beginning of the Happine&s;s of Believers&mdash;Chri&s;t is not only made to them Righteou&s;ne&s;s but <HI>Sanctification.</HI>&mdash;By Sanctification, I do <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> mean a bare hypocritical Attendance on outwar<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> Ordinances (tho' rightly-inform'd Chri&s;tians will think it their Duty and Privilege, con&s;tantly <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> attend on all outward Ordinances,) Nor do&punc; mean by Sanctification, a bare outward Refor|mation, and a few tran&s;ient Convictions, or a little legal Sorrow.&mdash;For all this an un&s;anctif<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters"> Man may have&mdash;But by Sanctification, I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> a total Renovation of the whole Man.&mdash;By <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Righteou&s;ne&s;s of Chri&s;t, Believers become <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> gally, by Sanctification, they are made <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> alive&mdash;By one they are entitled to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> made meet for Glory.&mdash;They <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> therefore throughout, in Spirit, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"></P>
