<P>Here then, O Believers! is one, tho' the lowe&s;t Degree of that Redemption, which you are to be Partakers of hereafter&mdash;I mean the Re|demption of your Bodies&mdash;For this Corruptible mu&s;t put on Incorruption, this Mortal mu&s;t put <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Immortality&mdash;Your Bodies as well as Souls were given to Je&s;us Chri&s;t by the Father&mdash;They
<PB N="146" REF="005311_0153_10181A2B23ABC278">
have been Companions in Watching, and Fa&s;ting&punc; and Praying&mdash;Your Bodies therefore, as well as Souls, &s;hall Je&s;us Chri&s;t rai&s;e up at the la&s;t Day&mdash;Fear not therefore, O Believers, to look into the Grave&mdash;For to you it is no other than a con&s;ecrated Dormitory, where your Bodies &s;hall &s;leep quietly till the Morning of the Re&s;ur|rection&mdash;When the Voice of the Archangel &s;hall &s;ound, and the Trump of God give the ge|neral Alarm, <HI>Ari&s;e ye Dead, and come to Judg|ment,</HI> Earth, Air, Fire, Water, &s;hall give up your &s;cattered Atoms, and both in Body and Soul &s;hall you be ever with the Lord&mdash;I doubt not but many of you are groaning under crazy Carca&s;&s;es, and complain often that the mortal Body weight down the immortal Soul&mdash;At lea&s;t this is my Ca&s;e&mdash;But let us have a little Patience, and we &s;hall be delivered from our earthly Pri&s;ons&mdash;'Ere it be long the&s;e Tabernacles of Clay &s;hall be di&s;&s;olved, and we &s;hall be cloathed with our Hou&s;e, which is from Heaven&mdash;Hereafter our Bodies &s;hall be &s;piritualized, and &s;hall be &s;o far from hindring our Souls through Weakne&s;s, that they &s;hall become &s;trong&mdash;So &s;trong, as to bear up under an exceeding and eternal Weight of Glory&mdash;Others again may have deformed Bo|dies, emaciated with Sickne&s;s, and worn out with Labour and Age&mdash;But wait a little, till your ble&s;&s;ed Change by Death comes&mdash;Then your Bodies &s;hall be renewed and made glorious, like unto Chri&s;t's glorious Body; of which we may form &s;ome faint Idea, from the Account given us of our Lord's Transfiguration on the
<PB N="147" REF="005311_0154_10181A2DB62CC640">
Mount, when it is &s;aid. <HI>His Raiment became <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">igh and gli<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">tering, and his Face brighter than <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">e Sun</HI>&mdash;Well then may a Believer break out <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">to the Apo&s;tle's triumphant Language,&mdash;<HI>O <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ath, where is thy Sting!&mdash;O Grave, where is t<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">y Victory!</HI></P>
<P>But what is the Redemption of the Body, in Compari&s;on of the Redemption of the better Part, our Souls?&mdash;I mu&s;t therefore &s;ay to you Believers, as the Angel &s;aid to <HI>John</HI>&mdash;Come up higher; and let us take as clear a View as we can at &s;uch a Di&s;tance, of the Redemption Chri&s;t has purcha&s;ed for, and will &s;hortly put you in actual Po&s;&s;e&s;&s;ion of&mdash;Already you are ju&s;tified, already you are &s;anctified, &amp; thereby freed from the Guilt and Dominion of Sin&mdash;But, as I ob|&s;erved before, the Being and In-dwelling of Sin yet remains in you&mdash;God &s;ees it proper to leave &s;ome <HI>Amalekites</HI> in the Land, to keep his <HI>I&s;rael</HI> in Action&mdash;The mo&s;t perfect Chri&s;tian, I am per&s;uaded, mu&s;t agree according to one of our Articles, <Q>that the Corruption of Nature re|mains even in the Regenerate; that the Fle&s;h lu&s;teth always again&s;t the Spirit, and the Spirit again&s;t the Fle&s;h</Q> So that Believers cannot Things for God with that Perfection they de&s;ire&mdash;This grieves their righteous Souls Day by Day&mdash;And with the holy Apo&s;tle makes them to cry out, <Q><HI>Who &s;hall deliver us from the Body of this Death!</HI></Q> I thank God, our Lord Je&s;us Chri&s;t, but not compleatly before the Day of our Di&s;&s;olution. Then will the very Being of Sin be de&s;troyed, and an eternal Stop
<PB N="148" REF="005311_0155_10181A2FC9F13250">
put to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, indwelling Corruption. And is not this a great Redemption I am &s;ure Be|lievers e&s;teem it &s;o&mdash;For there is nothing grieves the Heart of a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of God &s;o much, as the Remains of indwelling Sin&mdash;Again, Believers are often in He<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ine&s;s through manifold Temp|tations&mdash;God <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> that it is needful and good for them &s;o to be. And tho' they may be highly favoured, and wr<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">pt up in Communion with God, even to the third Heavens, yet a Me&s;&s;enger of Satan is often &s;ent to buffet them, l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t they &s;hould be puffed up with the Abundance of Re|velations&mdash;But <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e not weary, Be not faint in your Minds&mdash;The Time of your compleat Re|demption draw<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">th nigh&mdash;In Heaven the wicked One &s;hall cea&s;e from troubling you, and your weary Souls &s;hall enjoy an everla&s;ting Re&s;t&mdash;His fiery Darts cannot reach tho&s;e bli&s;sful Re|g<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">us&mdash;Satan will never come any more to appear with, di&s;turb, or accu&s;e the Sons of God, when once the Lord Je&s;us Chri&s;t &s;huts the Door&mdash;Your righteous Souls are now grieved, Day by Day, at the ungodly Conver&s;ation of the Wicked&mdash;Ta<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">es now grow up among the Wheat&mdash;Wolves come in Sheeps Cloathing&mdash;But the Redemption &s;poken of in the Text will free your Souls from all Anxiety on the&s;e Accounts&mdash;Hereafter you &s;hall enjoy a perfect Communion of Saints&mdash;Nothing that is unholy or un&s;anctified &s;hall enter into the Holy of Holies, which is pre|pared for you above&mdash;This, and all Manner of Evil what&s;oever, you &s;hall be delivered from when your Redemption is hereafter made com|pleat
<PB N="149" REF="005311_0156_10181A328C893A80">
in Heaven&mdash;Not only &s;o, but you &s;hall enter into the full Enjoyment of all Good&mdash;It's true&punc; all Saints will not have the &s;ame Degree of Happine&s;s, but all will be as happy as their Hearts can hold&mdash;Believers, you &s;hall judge Evil, and familiarly conver&s;e with good Ang<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">s&mdash;You &s;hall &s;it down with <HI>Abraham, I&s;aac, Jacob,</HI> and all the Spirits of ju&s;t Men made perfect&mdash;And to &s;um up all your Happine&s;s, in one Word, you &s;hall &s;ee God the Father, Son, and Holy Gho&s;t&mdash;And by &s;eeing <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, be more and more like him, and pa&s;s from Glory to Glory, even to all Eternity.</P>
<P>But I mu&s;t &s;top&mdash;The Glories of the upper World crowd in &s;o fa&s;t upon my Soul, that I am l<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t in the Contemplation of them.&mdash;Brethren, the Redemption &s;poken of is unutterable; we can|not here find it out&mdash;Eye hath not &s;een, nor Ear heard, nor has it entered into the Hearts of the mo&s;t holy Men living, to conceive how great it is. Was I to entertain you whole Ages with an Account of it, when you come to Heaven, you m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t &s;ay with <HI>Sheba, Not Half, no, not one Thou&s;andth Part was told us.</HI> All we can do here, is to go upon <HI>Mount Pi&s;gah,</HI> and by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Eye of Faith, take a di&s;tant View of the pro|mi&s;ed Land&mdash;We may &s;ee it, as <HI>Abraham</HI> did Chri&s;t, afar off and rejoice in it, but here we only know in part&mdash;Ble&s;&s;ed be God, there is a Time coming, when we &s;hall know God, even as we are known, &amp; God be all in all. <Q>Lord Je&s;us&punc; accompli&s;h the Number of thine Elect! Lord <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 words"> thy Kingdom.</Q></P>
<P><PB N="150" REF="005311_0157_10181A3765ED9458">
And now, where are the Scoffers of the&s;e la&s;t Days, who count the Lives of Chri&s;tians Mad|ne&s;s, and their End to be without Honour? Unhappy Men! you know not what you do. Were your Eyes open, and had you Sen&s;es to di&s;cern <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Things, you would not &s;peak all Manner of Evil again&s;t the Children of God, but you would e&s;teem them as the excellent Ones of the Earth, and envy their Happine&s;s: Your Souls would hunger and thir&s;t after it&mdash;You al&s;o would become Fools for Chri&s;t's Sake&mdash;You boa&s;t of Wi&s;dom; &s;o did the Philo&s;ophers of <HI>Corinth&punc;</HI> But your Wi&s;dom is the Fooli&s;hne&s;s of Folly in the Sight of God. What will your Wi&s;dom avail you, if it does not make you wi&s;e unto Salvation? Can you, with all your Wi&s;|dom, propo&s;e a more con&s;i&s;tent Scheme to build your Hopes of Salvation on, than what has been now laid down before you?&mdash;Can you, with all the Strength of natural Rea&s;on, find out a better Way of Acceptance with God, than by the Righteou&s;ne&s;s of the Lord Je&s;us Chri&s;t? Is it right to think your own Works can in any Mea&s;ure de&s;erve or procure it? If not, Why will you not believe in him? Why will you not &s;ubmit to his <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s?</HI> Can you deny that you are fallen Creatures? Do not you find that you are full of Di&s;orders, and that the&s;e Di&s;orders make you unhappy? Do not you find that you cannot change your own Hearts? Have you not re&s;olved many and many a Time, and have not your Corruptions yet Dominion over you? Are you not Bond-Slaves
<PB N="151" REF="005311_0158_10181A38FB004368">
to your <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, and led Captive by the Devil at his Will? Wh<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n will you not come to Chri&s;t for <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">?</HI> Do you not de&s;ire to die the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Righteous, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> your <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> like theirs? I am per&s;uaded <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Thoughts of being annihil<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ed, much le&s;s of being mi&s;erable for ever. Whatever you may pretend, if you &s;peak Truth, you mu&s;t confe&s;s, that Con&s;cience <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">reaks in upon you in your more &s;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ber Intervals whether you will or not, and even con&s;trains <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to believe that Hell is no painted Fire&mdash;And why then will you not come to Chri&s;t? He alone can procure you <HI>everla&s;ting Redemption</HI>&mdash;Ha&s;te, ha&s;te away to him, poor beguiled Sin|ners&mdash;You lack Wi&s;dom&mdash;A&s;k it of Chri&s;t, who knows but he may give it you? He is able&punc; For He is the Wi&s;dom of the Father&mdash;He is that Wi&s;dom which was from Everla&s;ting. You have no Righteou&s;ne&s;s, away to Chri&s;t&mdash;He is the End of the Law for Righteou&s;ne&s;s to every one that believeth&mdash;You are unholy&mdash;Fly to the Lord Je&s;us&mdash;He is full of Grace and Truth, and of his Fulne&s;s all may receive that believe in him&mdash;You are afraid to die&mdash;Let this drive you to Chri&s;t, He has the Keys of Death and Hell&mdash;In him is <HI>plenteous Redemption</HI>&mdash;He alone can open the Door which leads to everla&s;ting Life&mdash;Let not therefore the deceived Rea&s;oner boa&s;t any longer of his pretended Rea&s;on&mdash;Whatever you may <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, it is the mo&s;t unrea|&s;onable Thing in the World, not to believe on Je&s;us Chri&s;t, whom God hath &s;ent&mdash;Why, why
<PB N="152" REF="005311_0159_10181A3D986FC490">
will you die? Why will you not come unto him, that you may have Life? Ho, every one that thir&s;teth&punc; come unto the Waters of Life and drink freely&mdash;Come buy without Money and without Price&mdash;Were the&s;e ble&s;&s;ed Privi|leges in the Text to be purcha&s;ed by Money, you might &s;ay, we are poor and cannot buy&mdash;Or were they to be conferr'd only on Sinners of &s;uch a Rank or Degree, then you might &s;ay, how can &s;uch Sinners as we expect to be &s;o highly favoured? But they are to be freely given of God to the wor&s;t of Sinners&mdash;To us, &s;ays the Apo&s;tle&mdash;To me a Per&s;ecutor, to you <HI>Corinthi|ans,</HI> who were Unclean, Drunkards, covetous Per&s;ons, Idolaters&mdash;Therefore each poor Sinner may &s;ay then, Why not unto me? Has Chri&s;t but one Ble&s;&s;ing? What if he has ble<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ed Millions, by turning them from their Iniquities, yet he &s;till continues the &s;ame&mdash;He lives for ever to make Interce&s;&s;ion, and therefore will ble&s;s you, even you al&s;o&punc; tho' <HI>E&s;au</HI> like, you have been prophane, and hitherto de&s;pi&s;ed your heavenly Father's Birth-right&mdash;Even now, if you believe, Chri&s;t will be made to you of God, <HI>Wi&s;dom, Righteou&s;ne&s;s, Sanctification,</HI> and <HI>Redemption.</HI></P>
<P>But I mu&s;t turn again to Believers, for who&s;e In&s;truction, as I ob&s;erved before, this Di&s;cour&s;e was particularly intended&mdash;You &s;ee Brethren, Partakers of the heavenly Calling, what great Ble&s;&s;ings are trea&s;ured up for you in Je&s;us Chri&s;t your Head, and what you are entitled to by be|lieving on his Name&mdash;Take heed therefore, that ye walk worthy of the Vocation wherewith ye
<PB N="153" REF="005311_0160_10181A4063A83C20">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> called&mdash;Think often how highly you are <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, and remember you have not cho&s;en <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, but Chri&s;t hath cho&s;en you. Put on (as <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of God) H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">mblene&s;s of Mind, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, but Oh, let it be only <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n the Lord&mdash;For <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> have nothing but what you have received or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&punc; By Nature ye were as fooli&s;h, as legal, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, and in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s damnable a Condition as <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;Be pitiful therefore, be courteous, and Sanctification is a progre&s;&s;ive Work, beware <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> thinking you have already attained.&mdash;Let him <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> is holy, be holy &s;till&punc; knowing that he who <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t pure in Heart, &s;hall hereafter enjoy the cleare&s;t Vi&s;ion of God&mdash;Let indwelling Sin be your daily Burthen, and not only bewail and lament, but &s;ee that you &s;ubdue it daily by the Power of Divine Grace, and look up to Je&s;us continually to be the Fini&s;her, as well as Author of your Faith&mdash;Build not on your own Faith|fulne&s;s, but on God's Unchangeablene&s;s&mdash;Take Heed of thinking you &s;tand by the Power of your own Free-will&mdash;The everla&s;ting Love of God the Father mu&s;t be your only Hope and Con&s;o|lation&mdash;Let this &s;upport you under all Trials&mdash;Remember that God's Gifts and Callings are without Repentance&mdash;That Chri&s;t having once loved you, will have you to the End&mdash;Let this con&s;train <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">u to Obedience, and make you long and look for that ble&s;&s;ed Time, when he &s;hall not only be your <HI>Wi&s;dom,</HI> and <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;s&punc;</HI> and <HI>Sanctification,</HI> but al&s;o compleat and everla&s;ting <HI>Redemption.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Glory be to God in the Highe&s;t.</HI></P>
</DIV1>
<DIV1 N="7" TYPE="sermon">
<PB N="154" REF="005311_0161_10181A43596407D0">
<HEAD>SERMON VII.</HEAD>
<HEAD>The Phari&s;ee and Publican.</HEAD>
<EPIGRAPH>
<BIBL>LUKE xviii. 14.</BIBL>
<Q><HI>I tell you this Man went down to his Hou&s;e ju&s;tified rather than the other. For every one that exalteth him&s;elf &s;hall be ab<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;ed, and he that humbleth him&s;elf &s;hall be ex|alted.</HI></Q>
</EPIGRAPH>
<P>THO' there be &s;ome who dare wholly deny the Lord Je&s;us, and di&s;believe the Revelation he has been plea&s;ed to give us, and thereby bring upon them&s;elves &s;wift De|&s;truction, yet I would charitably hope there are but few, if any &s;uch among you, to whom I am now to <HI>preach the Kingdom of God</HI>&mdash;Was I do a&s;k you, <Q>How you expect to be ju&s;tified in the Sight <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> an offended God?</Q> I &s;uppo&s;e you would an&s;wer, only for the Sake of <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Lord Je&s;us Chri&s;t&mdash;But was I to come more home to your Con&s;ciences, I fear mo&s;t would make the Lord Je&s;us but in part their Saviour, and go
<PB N="155" REF="005311_0162_10181A45DF456EA0">
about, as it were, to e&s;tabli&s;h a Righteou&s;ne&s;s of their own&mdash;I believe this is not a thinking <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to the Rules of Chri&s;tian Charity&mdash;For we are all &s;elf-righteous by Nature&mdash;It is as natural for us to turn back to a Covenant of Works, as for the Sparks to fly upwards&mdash;We have had &s;o many legal, and &s;o few Free-grace Preachers for the&s;e many Years, that mo&s;t Pro|fe&s;&s;ors now &s;eem to be &s;ettled upon their Lees, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> rather de&s;erve the Title o<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Phari&s;ees</HI> than Chri&s;tians.</P>
<P>Thus it was with the Generality of the Peo|ple during the Time of our Lord's public Mini|&s;trations. And therefore, in almo&s;t all his Di&s;|cour&s;es, he preached the Go&s;pel to poor Sinners, and denounced terrible Woes again&s;t proud, S<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">lf-Ju&s;ticia<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">es&mdash;The Parable, to which the Words of the Text belong, looks both the&s;e Ways&mdash;For the Evangeli&s;t informs us, (<HI>Ver.</HI> 9.) that our Lord <HI>&s;pake it unto certain that tru&s;ted in them&s;elves that they were righteous, and di&s;pi&s;ed others</HI>&mdash;And a notable Parable it is&mdash;A Parable worthy your mo&s;t &s;erious Attention&mdash;<HI>He that hath Ears to hear, let him hear</HI> what Je&s;us Chri&s;t &s;peaks to all vi&s;ible Profe&s;&s;ors in it.</P>
<P><HI>Ver.</HI> 10. <Q><HI>Two Men,</HI> &s;ays our Lord, <HI>w<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n up to the Temple to pray,</HI> (and never <HI>two</HI> Men of more oppo&s;ite Characters) <HI>the one a Pha|ri&s;ee, and the other a Publican</HI></Q>&mdash;The <HI>Pha|ri&s;ees</HI> were the &s;tricte&s;t Sect among the <HI>Jews</HI>&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> was of the &s;tricte&s;t Sect of the <HI>Phari&s;ees,</HI> &s;ay&punc; St. <HI>Paul</HI>&mdash;They prayed often, not only &s;o&punc; but they made long Prayers, and that they might ap|pear
<PB N="156" REF="005311_0163_10181A47756C1620">
extraordinary devout, they would <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Corners of the Street, where two <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> that People going or coming, both Way, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ee them&mdash;They made broad, as our Lord <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> forms us, the Borders of their <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, i. e.</HI> they had Pieces of Parchment &s;own to their <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Robes (which we are told they <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">) on <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ome Parts of the Scripture were written, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> People might from thence infer, that they were Lovers of the Law of God. They were very punctual and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in outward Purifications, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> that they wa&s;hed at their <HI>going out and coming in</HI>&mdash;They held the Wa&s;hing of Pots, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Ve&s;&s;els, and Tables, and many other &s;uch like Things they did&mdash;They were very zealous for the Tradition of the Fathers, and for the Ob|&s;ervation of the Rites and Ceremonies of the Church, notwith&s;tanding they frequently made void the Law of God by their Traditions&mdash;And they were &s;o exceeding exact in the outward Ob&s;ervation of the Sabbath, that they condem|ned our Lord for a little Clay with his Spittle, and called him a Sinner, and &s;aid, he was not of God, becau&s;e he had given Sight to a Man born blind, on the Sabbath Day&mdash;For the&s;e Rea&s;ons they were had in high Veneration among the Peo|ple, who were &s;adly mi&s;led by the&s;e blind Guides&mdash;They had therefore the uppermo&s;t Places in the Synagogues, and Greetings in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Places (which they loved dearly) and were called of Men, <HI>Rabbi, Rabbi</HI>&mdash;In &s;hort, they had &s;uch a Reputaton for Piety, that it became a Proverb
<PB N="157" REF="005311_0164_10181A4A0EB80930">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the <HI>Jews,</HI> that if there were but <HI>two</HI> Men <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the one of them m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;t be a <HI>Phari&s;ee.</HI></P>
<P><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the <HI>Publicans,</HI> it <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not &s;o with them&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> they were &s;ometimes <HI>Jews,</HI> or at lea&s;t <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the Gate</HI>&mdash;(For we find one here <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> up to the Temple)&mdash;But for the Gene|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="4 letters">ty I am apt to think they were <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI>&mdash;<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> they were Gatherers of the <HI>Roman</HI> Taxes, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to ama&s;s much Wealth (as appears by the Confe&s;&s;ion of <HI>Zaccheus,</HI> one of the chief of 'em) <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> wronging Men by fal&s;e Accu&s;ation. They were &s;o univer&s;ally infamous, that our Lord him|&s;elf tells his Di&s;ciples, the excommunicated Man &s;hould be to them as a <HI>Heathen</HI> Man, or a <HI>Publi|can</HI>&mdash;And the <HI>Phari&s;ees</HI> thought it a &s;ufficient impeachment of our Lord's Character, that he was a <HI>Friend to Publicans and Sinners, and went to &s;it down with them at Meat.</HI></P>
<P>But however they di&s;agreed in other Things, they agreed in this, <HI>viz.</HI> that Publick Wor&s;hip is a Duty incumbent upon all. For they both came up to the Temple&mdash;The very Heathens were Ob&s;ervers of Temple-Wor&s;hip. We have very early Notice of Men's &s;acrificing to, and calling upon the Name of the Lord in the Old Te&s;tament. And I find it no where contradicted in the New&mdash;Our Lord and his Apo&s;tles went up to the Temple, and we are commanded by <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Apo&s;tle, <HI>not to for&s;ake the a&s;&s;embling our &s;elves <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">,</HI> as the Manner of too many is in our <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ays; and &s;uch too, as would have us think <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of them, tho' they &s;eldom or never tread <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e Courts of the Lord's Hou&s;e&mdash;But tho' our
<PB N="158" REF="005311_0165_10181A4E1E06A540">
Devotions begin in our Clo&s;ets, they mu&s;t not end there&mdash;And if People never &s;hew their De|votions abroad, I mu&s;t &s;u&s;pect they have little <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> none at Home&mdash;<HI>"Two Men went up to the Temple."</HI> And what went they thither for <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Not (<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Multitudes among us do) to make the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> God a <HI>Hou&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"></HI> or turn it into a <HI>Den of Thieves,</HI> much le&s;s to <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the Preacher, or di&s;turb the Congregation. No, they came to the Temple, &s;ays our Lord, <HI>to pray.</HI> For thither &s;hould the Tribes of God's <HI>&s;piritual I&s;rael</HI> go up to talk with, and pour out their Hearts before the mighty God of <HI>Jacob.</HI></P>
<P><HI>"Two Men went up to the Temple to pray"</HI>&mdash;I <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ear one of them forgot his Errand&mdash;I have often been at a Le&s;s what to call the <HI>Phari&s;ee'</HI>s Ad|dre&s;s&mdash;It certainly does not de&s;erve the Name of a Prayer&mdash;He may rather be &s;aid to come to the Temple to boa&s;t, than <HI>to pray</HI>&mdash;For I do not and one Word of Confe&s;&s;ion of his original Guilt.&mdash;Not one &s;ingle Petition for Pardon of his pa&s;t actual Sins, or for Grace to help and a&s;&s;i&s;t him for the Time to come&mdash;He only brings in God as it were a Reckoning of his Performance and does that, which no Fle&s;h can ju&s;tly do, I mean glory in his Pre&s;ence.</P>
<P><HI>Ver.</HI> 11. <HI>The Phari&s;ee &s;tood, and prayed thus with him&s;elf&mdash;God I thank thee that I am <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> other Men are, Extortioners, Unju&s;t, Adulter<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> or even as this Publican.</HI></P>
<P>Our Lord fir&s;t takes Notice of his Po&s;ture <HI>The Phari&s;ee &s;tood,</HI> &amp;c. He is not to be con|demned for that&mdash;For &s;tanding, as well as kneel&mdash;
<PB N="159" REF="005311_0166_10181A50ACAFE548">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, is a proper Po&s;ture <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Prayer. When you <HI><GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> praying,</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">&mdash;Tho' &s;ometimes our Lord kneeled, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> on his Face upon the Ground&mdash;His Apo&s;tles al&s;o kneeled, as we <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in the <HI>Acts</HI>&mdash;Which has made me wonder <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;ome, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> &s;o <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to &s;tandin<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> in Fa|mily, as well as publick Prayer, that they will not kneel, notwith&s;tanding <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> kneel that are around them. I fear there <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;omething of the <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> in this Conduct&mdash;Kneeling and &s;tand|ing are indifferent, if the Knee of the Soul be bent, and the Heart upright towards God. We &s;hould &s;tudy not to be particular in indifferent Things, le&s;t we offend weak Mind&punc;&mdash;What th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> is remarked for, is his <HI>&s;tanding by him|&s;elf</HI>&mdash;For the Words may be render'd, he &s;tood <HI>by him&s;elf</HI> upon &s;ome eminent Place, at the upper Part of the Temple, near the <HI>Holy of Holies,</HI> that the Congregation might &s;ee what a devout Man he was&mdash;Or it may be under&s;tood as we read it&mdash;He prayed by him&s;elf, or of him&s;elf, out of his own Heart&mdash;He did not pray by Form&mdash;It was an <HI>Extempore</HI> Prayer&mdash;For there are many <HI>Phari&s;ees</HI> that pray and preach too <HI>Extempore</HI>&mdash;I do not &s;ee why the&s;e may not be acquired, as well as other Arts and Sciences&mdash;A Man, with a good Elocution, ready Turn of Thought&punc; and good Memory, may repeat his own or other Mens Sermons, and by the Help of a <HI>Wilkins</HI> or <HI>Hea<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">,</HI> may pray &s;eemingly excellently well, and yet not have the lea&s;t Grain of true Grace in his Heart&mdash;And I &s;peak this not to cry down <HI>Ex|tempore</HI> Prayer, or to di&s;courage tho&s;e dear Souls
<PB N="160" REF="005311_0167_10181A52614DE8D0">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> pray by the Spirit&mdash;I only would <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> give a Word of Repro<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">f to th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">&s;e <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Prayer, that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> that u&s;e Forms, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> only as others <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> wrong&mdash;Not <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> one that prays <HI>Extempore</HI> is a &s;piritual, nor <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> one that prays with a Form, a formal M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n&mdash;Let us not judge one <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;Let not him that u&s;e a Form, judge him that prays <HI>Extem|pore,</HI> on that Acc<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">nt&punc; and let not him that prays <HI>Extempore,</HI> de&s;pi&s;e him that u&s;es a F<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">rm <HI>The Phari&s;ee &s;tood and prayed th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">s by him <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"></HI> Which may &s;ignify al&s;o praying inwardly in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Heart&mdash;For there i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> a Way (and that an excel|lent One too) of praying when we cannot &s;peak&mdash;Thus <HI>H<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="3 letters">ah</HI> prayed when &s;he &s;poke not out aloud, only her Lips m<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ved&mdash;Thus God &s;ays to <HI>Mo&s;es, Why cryed then,</HI> when it is plain, he did not &s;peak a Word. This is what the Apo&s;|tle means by the <HI>Spirit making Inter<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">&s;&s;ion for Believers, with Groani<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">s which cannot <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span">.</HI> For there are Times when the Soul is too big to &s;peak&mdash;When God fill it as it were and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hadows it with his Pre&s;ence, &s;o that it can only fall down, wor&s;hip, adore, and lie in the Du&s;t before the Lord&mdash;Again, there is a Time when the Soul is benumbed, barren, and dry, and the Believer has not a Word to &s;ay to his dear hea|venly Father&punc; and then the Heart only can &s;peak. And I mention this for the Encouragement of weak Chri&s;tians, who think they never are ac|cepted, but when they have a Flow of Words,
<PB N="161" REF="005311_0168_10181A558FC8AE10">
and fancy they do not plea&s;e God at the Bottom, for no other Rea&s;on, but becau&s;e they do not plea&s;e them&s;elves&mdash;Such would do well to con|&s;ider, that God knows the Language of the Heart and the Mind of the Spirit, and that we make U&s;e of Words, not to inform God, but to affect our&s;elves&mdash;Whenever therefore any of you find your&s;elves in &s;uch a Frame, be not di&s;couraged&mdash;Offer your&s;elves up in Silence before God, as Clay in the Hands of the Potter, for him <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">o write and &s;tamp his own divine Image upon your Souls&mdash;But I believe the <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> knew nothing of this Way of Prayer&mdash;He was &s;elf-righteous, a Stranger to the divine Life, and therefore eithe<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> of the forme. Explanations may be be&s;t put upon the&s;e Words&mdash;<Q><HI>He &s;tood, and prayed thus with him&s;elf&mdash;God I thank thee that I am not <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">as other Men are, Ext<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">rtioner, Unju&s;t, Adulterer, or even as this Publican</HI></Q>&mdash;Here is &s;ome Ap|pearance of Devotion, but it is only in Appear|ance&mdash;To thank God that we are not <HI>Ex<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">rti|eners, Unju&s;t, Adulterers,</HI> and as wicked in our Practices as other Men are, is certainly me<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> right, and our bounden Duty. For whatever Degrees of Goodne&s;s there may be in us, more than in others, it is owing to God's re&s;training, preventing, and a&s;&s;i&s;ting Grace&mdash;We are all equally conceived and born in Sin&mdash;All equally fallen &s;hort of the Glory of God, and <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> to all the Cur&s;es and Maledictions of the Law, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> that he that glorieth, mu&s;t glory only in the Lord&mdash;For none of us have any thing which we did not receive; and whatever we have recei|ved,
<PB N="162" REF="005311_0169_10181A5ABB6DD248">
we did not in the lea&s;t merit it, or could we lay the lea&s;t Claim to it on any Account whatever&mdash;We are wholly indebted to <HI>Free Grace</HI> for all&mdash;Had the <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> thought thus&punc; when he &s;aid, <HI>"God I thank thee that I am not as other Men are,"</HI> it would have been an ex|cellent Introduction to his Prayer&mdash;But he was a Free-willer, as well as &s;elf-righteous (for he that is one, mu&s;t be the other) and thought by his own Power and Strength, he had kept him&s;elf from the&s;e Vices&mdash;And yet I do not <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> what Rea&s;on he had to tru&s;t in him&s;elf that he was righteous, merely becau&s;e he was not an <HI>Extortioner, Unju&s;t, Adulterer</HI>&mdash;For all this while he might be, as he certainly was, (as is al&s;o every &s;elf-righteous Per&s;on) as proud as the De|vil&mdash;But he not only boa&s;ts, but lies before God (as all Self-ju&s;ticaries will be found Liars here or hereafter.) He thanks God that he was not <HI>Unju&s;t</HI>&mdash;But is it not an Act of the highe&s;t Inju&s;tice to rob God of his Prerogative? Is it not an Act of Inju&s;tice to judge our Neigh|bour? And yet of both the&s;e Crimes this &s;elf-righteous Vaunter is guilty&mdash;<HI>Even as this Pub|lican</HI>&mdash;He &s;eems to &s;peak with the utmo&s;t Di&s;|dain&mdash;<HI>This Publican,</HI> perhaps he pointed at the poor Man, that others might treat him with the like Contempt&mdash;Thou proud, confident Boa&s;ter&punc; What had&s;t thou to do with that <HI>poor Publican?</HI> Suppo&s;ing other <HI>Publicans</HI> were <HI>Unju&s;t,</HI> and <HI>Ex|tortioners,</HI> did it therefore follow that he mu&s;t be &s;o? Or if he had been &s;uch a Sinner, How knowe&s;t thou but he has repented of tho&s;e Sins<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">
<PB N="163" REF="005311_0170_10181A5C53E59508">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> coming up to the Temple to pray, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> one <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Sign of a Reformation at lea&s;t&mdash;Thou art therefore inexcu&s;able, <HI>O Phari&s;ee,</HI> who thus judge&s;t the <HI>Publican</HI>&mdash;For thou that judge&s;t him to be unju&s;t&punc; art in the very Act of judging, <HI>unju&s;t thy&s;elf</HI>&mdash;Thy Sacrifice <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> only the Sacri|fice of a Fool.</P>
<P>We have &s;een the<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> what the <HI>Phari&s;ee's</HI> nega|tive Goodne&s;s comes to; I think nothing at all&mdash;Let us &s;ee how far his po&s;itive Goodne&s;s ex|tends&mdash;For if we are truly religious, we &s;hall not only e&s;chew Evil, but al&s;o do Good&mdash;<Q><HI>I fa&s;t,</HI> &s;ays he, <HI>twice in the Week&mdash;I give Tithes of all that I po&s;&s;e&s;s.</HI></Q></P>
<P>The <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> is not here condemned for h<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters"> Fa&s;ting, for Fa&s;ting is a Chri&s;tian Duty&mdash;<HI>When you fa&s;t,</HI> &s;ays our Lord, thereby taking it for granted that his Di&s;ciples would fa&s;t&mdash;And <HI>when the bridegroom &s;hall be taken away, th<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n &s;hall they fa&s;t in tho&s;e Days. In fa&s;ting often,</HI> &s;ays the Apo&s;tle, and all that would not be Ca&s;t|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ways, will take Care, as their Privilege, with|out legal Con&s;traint, to <HI>keep their Bodies under, and bring them into Subjection:</HI> The <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> is only condemned for making a Righteou&s;ne&s;s of his Fa&s;ting, and thinking that God would ac|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">pt him, or that he was any better than his Neighbours merely on Account of his Fa&s;ting. This i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> what he is blamed for. The <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> not to be commended for fa&s;ting twice in <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Week&mdash;I wi&s;h Chri&s;tians would imitate him <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in this. But to depend on Fa&s;ting in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 span"> Ju&s;tification in the Sight of God,
<PB N="164" REF="005311_0171_10181A5E13A85940">
was really abominable. <Q><HI>I give Tythes of all that I po&s;&s;e&s;s.</HI></Q> He might as well have &s;aid, <HI>I pay Tythes</HI>&mdash;But Self-righteous People (what|ever they may &s;ay to the contrary) think they <HI>give</HI> &s;omething to God&mdash;<HI>I give Tythes of all that I po&s;&s;e&s;s</HI>&mdash;I make Con&s;cience of giving Tythes, not only of all that the Law requires, but of my <HI>Mint, Annice,</HI> and <HI>Cummin,</HI> of all Things what|&s;oever that I po&s;&s;e&s;s&mdash;This was well. To pay Tythes when required by the Laws of the Land, is certainly our Duty&mdash;But to boa&s;t of &s;uch Things, or of Fa&s;ting, is <HI>Phari&s;aical</HI> &amp; Devili&s;h. And now then let us &s;um up all the Righteou&s;|ne&s;s of this boa&s;ting <HI>Phari&s;ee,</HI> and &s;ee what little Rea&s;on he had to <HI>tru&s;t in him&s;elf that he was righteou<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">,</HI> or to de&s;pi&s;e others. He is not <HI>Un|ju&s;t,</HI> (but we have only his ba<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">e Word for that, I think I have proved to the contrary.) He i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> no <HI>Adulterer,</HI> no <HI>Extortioner,</HI> he fa&s;ts <HI>twice in the Week,</HI> and <HI>gives Tythes of all that he po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es.</HI>&mdash;And all this he might do, and a great deal more, and yet be a Child of the Devil. For here is no Mention made of his loving the Lord his God with all his Heart, which was the <HI>fir&s;t and great Commandment of the Law.</HI>&mdash;Here's not a &s;ingle Syllable of inward Religion&mdash;And he was not a true Jew, who was only one outwardly. And 'tis only an out&s;ide Piety at the be&s;t&mdash;In|wardly he is full of Pride, Self-Ju&s;tification, Free-will, and great Uncharitablene&s;s.</P>
<P>Were not the <HI>Phari&s;ees,</HI> do you think, highly offended at this Character? For they might ea&s;ily know it was &s;poken again&s;t them&punc; And
<PB N="165" REF="005311_0172_10181A61085F0160">
tho' perhaps &s;ome of you may be offended at me, yet out of Love I mu&s;t tell you, I fear this Para|ble is &s;poken again&s;t many of you.&mdash;For are there not many of you, who go up to the Tem|ple to pray, with no better Spirit than this <HI>Pha|ri&s;ee</HI> did? And becau&s;e you fa&s;t, it may be in the <HI>Lent,</HI> or every <HI>Friday,</HI> and becau&s;e you do No-body any Harm, receive the Sacrament, pay Tythes, give an Alms now and then, think that you are &s;afe, and tru&s;t in your&s;elves that you are righteous, and inwardly de&s;pi&s;e tho&s;e, who do not come up to you in the&s;e outward Duties? This I am per&s;uaded is the Ca&s;e of many of you, tho' alas! it is a de&s;perate one, as I &s;hall endeavour to &s;hew at the Clo&s;e of this Di&s;|cour&s;e.</P>
<P>Let us now take a View of the <HI>Publican. Ver.</HI> 13. <HI>And the Publican &s;tanding afar off, would not lift up &s;o much as his Eyes unto Heaven, but &s;mote upon his Brea&s;t, &s;aying, God be merciful to me a Sinner.</HI></P>
<P>The <HI>Publican &s;tanding afar off</HI>&mdash;Perhaps in the outward Court of the Temple, con&s;cious to him&s;elf that he was not worthy to approach the Holy of Holies&mdash;So con&s;cious, and &s;o weighed down with a Sen&s;e of his own Unworthine&s;s, that he would not &s;o much as lift up his Eyes unto Heaven, which he knew was God's Throne&mdash;Poor Heart! what did he feel at this Time! None but <HI>Returning Publicans,</HI> like him&s;elf, can <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;Methinks I &s;ee him &s;tanding afar off, per|<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">ve, oppre&s;&s;ed, and even overwhelmed with Sorrow&mdash;Sometimes he attempts to look up&mdash;
<PB N="166" REF="005311_0173_10181A6522B0D430">
But then, thinks he, the Heavens are unclean in God's Sight, and the very Angels are charged with Folly, how then &s;hall &s;uch a Wretch <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> dare to lift up my guilty Head!&mdash;And to &s;hew that his Heart was full of holy Self-Re&s;entment, and that he &s;orrowed after a godly Sort, he &s;mote upon his Brea&s;t, the Word in the Original im|plies, that he <HI>&s;truck hard</HI> upon his Brea&s;t: For he will lay the Blame upon none but his own wicked Heart. He will not, like unhumbled <HI>Adam,</HI> tacitly lay the Fault of his Vilene&s;s upon God, and &s;ay, the <HI>Pa&s;&s;ions which thou gave&s;t me, they deceived me, and I &s;inned</HI>&mdash;He is too penitent thus to reproach his Maker&mdash;He &s;mites upon his Brea&s;t, his treacherous, ungreatful, de&s;pe|rately wicked Brea&s;t&mdash;A Brea&s;t now ready to bur&s;t, and at length, out of the Abundance of his Heart, I doubt not, with many Tears, he a<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">la&s;t crys out, <HI>God be merciful to me a Sinner</HI>&mdash;Not God be merciful to yonder proud <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI>&mdash;He found enough in him&s;elf to vent his Re|&s;entment again&s;t, without looking abroad upon others&mdash;Not God be merciful to me a Saint&mdash;For he knew all his <HI>Righteou&s;ne&s;&s;es were but filthy Rags</HI>&mdash;Not God be merciful to &s;uch or &s;uch a one, but God be merciful to me, even to me a Sinner&mdash;A Sinner by Birth&mdash;A Sinner in Thought, Word, and Deed&mdash;A Sinner as to my Per&s;on&mdash;A Sinner as to all my Performances&mdash;A Sinner in whom is no Health, in whom dwelleth no good Thing&mdash;A Sinner poor, mi&s;erable, blind and na|ked, from the Crown of the Head, to the Sole of the Feet, f<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ll of Wounds, and Brui&s;es, and
<PB N="167" REF="005311_0174_10181A685B1C6630">
<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">trifying Sores&mdash;A &s;elf-accu&s;ed, &s;elf-condem|ned Sinner&mdash;What think you? Would this <HI>Publican</HI> been offended if any Mini&s;ter had told <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> that he de&s;erved to be damned? Would he <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> been angry, if any one had told him, that <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Nature he was half a Devil and half a Bea&s;t?</P>
<P>He would have confe&s;&s;ed a thou&s;and Hells have been his due, and that he was an earthly, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">, devili&s;h Sinner&mdash;He felt now what a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">eadful Thing it was to depart from the living <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&mdash;He felt that he was inexcu&s;able every Way&mdash;that he could in no wi&s;e, upon Account <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">any Thing in him&s;elf, he ju&s;tified in the Sight <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> God&mdash;And therefore lays him&s;elf at the Feet <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;overeign Mercy, <HI>"God be merciful to me a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Sinner"</HI>&mdash;Here's no Confidence in the Fle&s;h, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Plea fetch'd from Fa&s;ting, paying Tythes, or <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Performance of any other Duty&mdash;Here's no <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="2 letters">a&s;ting, that he was not an <HI>Extortioner, Unju&s;t,</HI> or an <HI>Adulterer</HI>&mdash;Perhaps he had been guilty of all the&s;e Crimes, at lea&s;t he knew he &s;hould have <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> guilty of all the&s;e had he been left to follow the Devices and De&s;ires of his own Heart; and therefore, with a broken and contrite Spirit, he crys out, <HI>"God be merciful to me a Sinner."</HI></P>
<P>This Man came up to the Temple to pray, and he prayed indeed&mdash;And a broken and contrite Heart God will not de&s;pi&s;e. <HI>I tell you,</HI> &s;ays our Lord&mdash;I who lay in the Bo&s;om of the Father from all Eternity&mdash;I who am God, and there|fore know all Things&mdash;I who can neither de|ceive, nor be deceived, who&s;e Judgment is ac|cording to Right&mdash;<HI>I</HI> tell you, whatever <HI>you</HI> may
<PB N="168" REF="005311_0175_10181A6A73224D30">
think of it, or think of me for telling you &s;o, <HI>this Man, this Publican,</HI> this <HI>de&s;pi&s;ed, &s;inful,</HI> but <HI>broken-hearted</HI> Man, <HI>went down to his Hou&s;e ju&s;ti|fied</HI> (acquitted, and looked upon as Righteous in the Sight of God) <HI>rather than the other.</HI></P>
<P>Let <HI>Phari&s;ees</HI> take Heed that they do not per|vert this Text&mdash;For when it is &s;aid, <HI>this Man went down to his Hou&s;e ju&s;tified rather than the other</HI>&mdash;Our Lord does not mean that both were ju&s;tified, and that the <HI>Publican</HI> had rather more Ju&s;tification than the <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI>&mdash;But it implies, either that the <HI>Publican</HI> was actually ju&s;tified, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> the <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> was not; or, that the <HI>Publican</HI> <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> in a better Way for Ju&s;tification, or in a better Frame to receive it, than the <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI>&mdash;According to our Lord's Saying&mdash;<Q><HI>The Pub|licans and Harlots enter into the Kingdom of Heaven before you</HI></Q>&mdash;That the <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> was not ju&s;tified is certain&mdash;For God re&s;i&s;teth the Proud, and that the <HI>Publican</HI> was at this Time actually ju&s;tified (and perhaps went home with a Sen&s;e of it in his Heart) we have great Rea&s;on to infer from the latter Part of the Text&mdash;<Q><HI>For every one that exalteth him&s;elf &s;hall be aba&s;ed, and he that humbleth him&s;elf &s;hall be exalted.</HI></Q></P>
<P>The Parable therefore now &s;peaks to all that hear me this Day&mdash;For that our Lord intended it for our Learning is evident, from his making &s;uch a general Application&mdash;<HI>For every one,</HI> &s;ays he, <HI>that exalteth him&s;elf &s;hall be aba&s;ed, and he that humbleth him&s;elf &s;hall be exalted.</HI></P>
<P>The Parable of the <HI>Publican</HI> and <HI>Phari&s;ee</HI> is but as it were a Gla&s;s wherein we may &s;ee the
<PB N="169" REF="005311_0176_10181A6E0AFF00A0">
different Di&s;po&s;ition of all Mankind. For all Mankind may be divided into two general Cla&s;&s;es&punc;&mdash;Either they tru&s;t wholly in them&s;elves, or in Part, that they are righteous, and then they are <HI>Phari&s;ees;</HI> or they have no Confidence in the Fle&s;h, are &s;elf-condemned Sinners, and then they come under the Character of the <HI>Publican</HI> ju&s;t now di&s;cour&s;ed of&mdash;And we may add al&s;o, that the different Reception the&s;e M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n met with, points out to us in lively Colours, the different Treatment the &s;elf-ju&s;ticiary and &s;elf-condemned Criminal will meet with at the terrible Day of Judgment. <HI>Every one that exalts him&s;elf &s;hall be aba&s;ed, but he that humbleth him&s;elf &s;hall be exalted.</HI></P>
<P><HI>Every one,</HI> without Exception, Young or Old, High or Low, Rich or Poor (for God is no Re|&s;pecter of Per&s;ons) <HI>every one,</HI> who&s;oever he be, that exalteth him&s;elf, and not Free Grace, every one that tru&s;teth in him&s;elf that he is righteous, that re&s;ts in his Duties, or thinks to join them with the Righteou&s;ne&s;s of Je&s;us Chri&s;t for Ju&s;ti|fication in the Sight of God, tho' he be <HI>no Adul|terer, no Extortioner,</HI> tho' he be not outwardly <HI>Unju&s;t,</HI> nay, tho' he <HI>fa&s;t twice in the Week,</HI> and <HI>gives Tythes of all that he po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es,</HI> yet &s;hall he be aba&s;ed in the Sight of all good M<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n that know him here, and before Men and Angels, and God him&s;elf, when Je&s;us Chri&s;t comes to appear in Judgment hereafter? How low? None but the Almighty God can tell&mdash;He &s;hall be aba&s;ed to live with Devils, and make his Abode in the lowe&s;t Hell for evermore.</P>
<P><PB N="170" REF="005311_0177_10181A731B704EA8">
Hear this, all ye Self-Ju&s;ticiaries, tremble and behold your Doom!&mdash;A dreadful Doom, more dreadful than Words can expre&s;s, or Thought conceive&mdash;If you refu&s;e to humble your&s;elves, after hearing this Parable, I call Heaven and Earth to witne&s;s again&s;t you this Day, that God &s;hall vi&s;it you with all his Storms, and pour all the Vials of his Wrath upon your rebelli<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">us Heads&mdash;You exalted your&s;elves here, and God &s;hall aba&s;e you hereafter&mdash;You are as proud as the Devil, and with Devils &s;hall you dwell to all Eternity&mdash;Be not deceived&mdash;God is not mocked&mdash;He &s;ees your Hearts&mdash;He knows all Things&mdash;And, notwith&s;tanding you may come <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">p to the Temple to pray, your Prayers are turned into Sin, and you go down to your Hou&s;es unju&s;tified, if you are Self-Ju&s;ticiaries. And do you know what it is to be unju&s;tified? Why, if you are unju&s;tified, the Wrath of God abideth upon you. You are in your Blood&mdash;All the Cur&s;es of the Law belong to you. Cur&s;ed are you when you go out&mdash;Cur&s;ed are you when you come in&mdash;Cur&s;ed are your Thoughts, cur|&s;ed are your Words, cur&s;ed are your Deeds <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Every thing you do, &s;ay, or think, from Morning to Night, is only one continued Series of Sin. However highly you may be e&s;teemed in the Sight of Men&mdash;However you may be honoured with the uppermo&s;t Seats in the Synagogues in the Church militant, you will have no Place in the Church <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> Humble your&s;elves therefore under the mighty Hand of God&mdash;Pull down every &s;elf-righteous
<PB N="171" REF="005311_0178_10181A74B0C48710">
Thought, and every proud Imagination, that now exalteth it&s;elf again&s;t the perfect, per&s;onal, imputed Righteou&s;ne&s;s of the dear Lord Je&s;us&mdash;For he, and he alone that humbleth him&s;elf &s;hall be exalted.</P>
<P>He that humbleth him&s;elf, whatever he be. If in&s;tead of Fa&s;ting twice in the Week, he has got drunk twice in the Week&mdash;If in&s;tead of giving Tythes of all that he po&s;&s;e&s;&s;es, has cheated the Mini&s;ter of his Tythes, and King of his Taxes; notwith&s;tanding he be <HI>Unju&s;t, Extorti|oner, Adulterer,</HI> nay, notwith&s;tanding the Sins of all Mankind be center'd and united in him&punc; yet if through Grace, like the <HI>Publican,</HI> he i<GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter"> enabled to humble him&s;elf, he &s;hall be exalted&mdash;Not in a temporal Manner&mdash;For Chri&s;tians mu&s;t rather expect to be aba&s;ed, and to have their Names ca&s;t out as Evil, and to lay down their Lives for Chri&s;t Je&s;us in this World. But he &s;hall be exalted in a &s;piritual Sen&s;e&mdash;He &s;hall be freely ju&s;tified from all his Sins by the Blood of Je&s;us&mdash;He &s;hall have Peace with God, a Peace which pa&s;&s;eth all Under&s;tanding&mdash;Not only Peace, but Joy in Believing&mdash;He &s;hall be tran&s;|lated from the Kingdom of Satan, to the King|dom of God's dear Son&mdash;He &s;hall dwell in Chri&s;t, and Chri&s;t in him. He &s;hall be one with Chri&s;t, and Chri&s;t one with him. He &s;hall drink of divine Plea&s;ures, as out of a River. He &s;hall be &s;anctified throughout in Spirit, Soul and Body&punc; <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">n one&punc; Word, he &s;hall be filled with all the Ful|ne&s;s of God&mdash;Thus &s;hall the Man that humbleth him&s;elf be exalted here&mdash;But oh, how high &s;hall
<PB N="172" REF="005311_0179_10181A76C71E0D50">
he be exalted hereafter! As high as the highe&s;t Heavens, even to the Right-hand of God&mdash;There <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> &s;hall &s;it happy both in Soul and Body, and judge Angels, high out of the Reach of all Sin and Trouble, eternally &s;ecure from all Dan|ger of falling O Sinners, did you but know how highly God intends to exalt tho&s;e who humble them&s;elves, and believe in Je&s;us, &s;urely you would humble your&s;elves, at lea&s;t beg of God to hum|ble you&mdash;For it is he that mu&s;t &s;trike the Rock of your Hearts, &amp; cau&s;e Floods of contrite Tears to flow out there from. And Oh, that God would give this Sermon &s;uch a Commi&s;&s;ion, as he once gave the Rod of <HI>Mo&s;es!</HI> I would &s;trike you through and through with the Rod of his Word, <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word">&punc; each of you was brought to cry out with the poor <HI>Publican, God be merciful to me a Sinner</HI>&mdash;What Plea&s;ant Language would this be in the <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 letter">ars of the <HI>Lord of Sabbaoth!</HI> Are there no poor Sinners among you? What are you all <HI>Phari|&s;ees?</HI> Surely you cannot bear the Thoughts of returning home unju&s;tified, can you? What if a <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> of the Apoplexy &s;hould &s;eize you, and your Souls be hurried away before the awful Judge of Quick and Dead? What will you do without Chri&s;t's Righteou&s;ne&s;s? If you go out of the World unju&s;tified, you mu&s;t remain &s;o for ever. Oh, that you would humble your&s;elves, then would the Lord exalt you&mdash;It may be, that whil&s;t I am &s;peaking, the Lord might ju&s;tify you freely by his Grace&mdash;I ob&s;erved, that perhaps the <HI>Publican</HI> had a Sen&s;e of his Ju&s;tification <GAP DESC="illegible" RESP="AELD" EXTENT="1 word"> he went from the Temple, and know that
