<P>There's no &s;eeing Chri&s;t in Glory, unle&s;s we run before the Multitude, and are willing to be in the Number of tho&s;e de&s;pi&s;ed few, who take the Kingdom of God by Violence&mdash;That broad Way, in which &s;o many go, can never be that &s;trait and narrow Way which leads to Life&mdash;Our Lord's Flock was, and always will be, comparatively a little One&mdash;And unle&s;s we dare to run before the Multitude in a holy Sin|gularity, and can rejoyce in being accounted Fools for Chri&s;t's Sake, we &s;hall never &s;ee Je&s;us with Comfort, when he appears in Glory&mdash;From mentioning the Sycamore-Tree, and con&s;idering the Difficulty with which <HI>Zaccheus</HI> mu&s;t climb it, we may further learn, that tho&s;e who would &s;ee Chri&s;t, mu&s;t undergo other Difficulties and Hard&s;hips be&s;ides Contempt. <HI>Zaccheus,</HI> without doubt, went through both&mdash;Did not many, think you, laugh at him as he ran along, and in the Language of <HI>Michal, Saul'</HI>s Daughter, cry out, How glorious did the rich <HI>Zaccheus</HI> look to Day, when forgetting the Greatne&s;s of his Station, he ran before a pitiful, giddy Mob, and climbed up a Sycamore-Tree, to &s;ee an <HI>Enthu&s;ia&s;tick</HI> Preacher!&mdash;But <HI>Zaccheus</HI> cares not for all that&mdash;His Curio&s;ity was &s;trong&mdash;If he could but &s;ee who Je&s;us was, he did not value what Scoffers &s;aid of him&mdash;And thus much more will it be
